# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-hbase
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The core of Apache Hadoop consists of a storage part, known as Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS), and a processing part which is a MapReduce programming model.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Hadoop splits files into large blocks and distributes them across nodes in a cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] It then transfers packaged code into nodes to process the data in parallel.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] This approach takes advantage of data locality, where nodes manipulate the data they have access to.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] This allows the dataset to be processed faster and more efficiently than it would be in a more conventional supercomputer architecture that relies on a parallel file system where computation and data are distributed via high-speed networking.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Apache Hadoop's MapReduce and HDFS components were inspired by Google papers on MapReduce and Google File System.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop framework itself is mostly written in the Java programming language, with some native code in C and command line utilities written as shell scripts.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Perl language can be easily used with Hadoop Streaming to implement the map and reduce parts of the user's program.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] According to its co-founders, Doug Cutting and Mike Cafarella, the idea of Hadoop was conceived in the Google File System paper that was published in October 2003.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The concept was extended in the Google paper *"MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters".* Development started on the Apache Nutch project, but was moved to the new Hadoop subproject in January 2006.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Doug Cutting, who was working at Yahoo! at the time, named it after his son's toy elephant.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The initial code that was factored out of Nutch consisted of about 5,000 lines of code for HDFS and about 6,000 lines of code for MapReduce.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] In March 2006, Owen O'Malley was the first committer to add to the Hadoop project; Hadoop 0.1.0 was released in April 2006.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] It continues to evolve through contributions that are being made to the project.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The first design document for the Hadoop Distributed File System was written by Dhruba Borthakur in 2007.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Hadoop consists of the *Hadoop Common* package, which provides file system and operating system level abstractions, a MapReduce engine (either MapReduce/MR1 or YARN/MR2) and the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS).
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop Common package contains the Java Archive (JAR) files and scripts needed to start Hadoop.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] For effective scheduling of work, every Hadoop-compatible file system should provide location awareness, which is the name of the rack, specifically the network switch where a worker node is.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Hadoop applications can use this information to execute code on the node where the data is, and, failing that, on the same rack/switch to reduce backbone traffic.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] HDFS uses this method when replicating data for data redundancy across multiple racks.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] This approach reduces the impact of a rack power outage or switch failure; if any of these hardware failures occurs, the data will remain available.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] A small Hadoop cluster includes a single master and multiple worker nodes.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The master node consists of a Job Tracker, Task Tracker, NameNode, and DataNode.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] A slave or *worker node* acts as both a DataNode and TaskTracker, though it is possible to have data-only and compute-only worker nodes.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] These are normally used only in nonstandard applications.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Hadoop requires the Java Runtime Environment (JRE) 1.6 or higher.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The standard startup and shutdown scripts require that Secure Shell (SSH) be set up between nodes in the cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] In a larger cluster, HDFS nodes are managed through a dedicated NameNode server to host the file system index, and a secondary NameNode that can generate snapshots of the namenode's memory structures, thereby preventing file-system corruption and loss of data.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Similarly, a standalone JobTracker server can manage job scheduling across nodes.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop MapReduce is used with an alternate file system, the NameNode, secondary NameNode, and DataNode architecture of HDFS are replaced by the file-system-specific equivalents.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The *Hadoop distributed file system* (HDFS) is a distributed, scalable, and portable file system written in Java for the Hadoop framework.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] A Hadoop instance is divided into HDFS and MapReduce.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] HDFS is used for storing the data and MapReduce is used for processing data.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Top three are Master Services/Daemons/Nodes and bottom two are Slave Services.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Master Services can communicate with each other and in the same way Slave services can communicate with each other.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Name Node is a master node and Data node is its corresponding Slave node and can talk with each other.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Hadoop cluster has nominally a single namenode plus a cluster of datanodes, although redundancy options are available for the namenode due to its criticality.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Each datanode serves up blocks of data over the network using a block protocol specific to HDFS.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The file system uses TCP/IP sockets for communication.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Clients use remote procedure calls (RPC) to communicate with each other.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] HDFS stores large files (typically in the range of gigabytes to terabytes) across multiple machines.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] It achieves reliability by replicating the data across multiple hosts, and hence theoretically does not require redundant array of independent disks (RAID) storage on hosts (but to increase input-output (I/O) performance some RAID configurations are still useful).
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] With the default replication value, 3, data is stored on three nodes: two on the same rack, and one on a different rack.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Data nodes can talk to each other to rebalance data, to move copies around, and to keep the replication of data high.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] HDFS is not fully POSIX-compliant, because the requirements for a POSIX file-system differ from the target goals of a Hadoop application.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The trade-off of not having a fully POSIX-compliant file-system is increased performance for data throughput and support for non-POSIX operations such as Append.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] In May 2012, high-availability capabilities were added to HDFS, letting the main metadata server called the NameNode manually fail-over onto a backup.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The project has also started developing automatic fail-overs.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The HDFS file system includes a so-called *secondary namenode*, a misleading term that some might incorrectly interpret as a backup namenode when the primary namenode goes offline.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] In fact, the secondary namenode regularly connects with the primary namenode and builds snapshots of the primary namenode's directory information, which the system then saves to local or remote directories.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] These checkpointed images can be used to restart a failed primary namenode without having to replay the entire journal of file-system actions, then to edit the log to create an up-to-date directory structure.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Because the namenode is the single point for storage and management of metadata, it can become a bottleneck for supporting a huge number of files, especially a large number of small files.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] HDFS Federation, a new addition, aims to tackle this problem to a certain extent by allowing multiple namespaces served by separate namenodes.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Moreover, there are some issues in HDFS such as small file issues, scalability problems, Single Point of Failure (SPoF), and bottlenecks in huge metadata requests.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] One advantage of using HDFS is data awareness between the job tracker and task tracker.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The job tracker schedules map or reduce jobs to task trackers with an awareness of the data location.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] For example: if node A contains data (a, b, c) and node X contains data (x, y, z), the job tracker schedules node A to perform map or reduce tasks on (a, b, c) and node X would be scheduled to perform map or reduce tasks on (x, y, z).
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] This reduces the amount of traffic that goes over the network and prevents unnecessary data transfer.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop is used with other file systems, this advantage is not always available.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] This can have a significant impact on job-completion times as demonstrated with data-intensive jobs.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] HDFS was designed for mostly immutable files and may not be suitable for systems requiring concurrent write operations.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] HDFS can be mounted directly with a Filesystem in Userspace (FUSE) virtual file system on Linux and some other Unix systems.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] File access can be achieved through the native Java API, the Thrift API (generates a client in a number of languages e.g.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] C++, Java, Python, PHP, Ruby, Erlang, Perl, Haskell, C#, Cocoa, Smalltalk, and OCaml), the command-line interface, the HDFS-UI web application over HTTP, or via 3rd-party network client libraries.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] HDFS is designed for portability across various hardware platforms and for compatibility with a variety of underlying operating systems.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The HDFS design introduces portability limitations that result in some performance bottlenecks, since the Java implementation cannot use features that are exclusive to the platform on which HDFS is running.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Due to its widespread integration into enterprise-level infrastructure, monitoring HDFS performance at scale has become an increasingly important issue.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Monitoring end-to-end performance requires tracking metrics from datanodes, namenodes, and the underlying operating system.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] There are currently several monitoring platforms to track HDFS performance, including Hortonworks, Cloudera, and Datadog.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Hadoop works directly with any distributed file system that can be mounted by the underlying operating system by simply using a `file://` URL; however, this comes at a price – the loss of locality.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] To reduce network traffic, Hadoop needs to know which servers are closest to the data, information that Hadoop-specific file system bridges can provide.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] A number of third-party file system bridges have also been written, none of which are currently in Hadoop distributions.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] However, some commercial distributions of Hadoop ship with an alternative file system as the default – specifically IBM and MapR.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Atop the file systems comes the MapReduce Engine, which consists of one *JobTracker*, to which client applications submit MapReduce jobs.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The JobTracker pushes work to available *TaskTracker* nodes in the cluster, striving to keep the work as close to the data as possible.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] With a rack-aware file system, the JobTracker knows which node contains the data, and which other machines are nearby.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] If the work cannot be hosted on the actual node where the data resides, priority is given to nodes in the same rack.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] This reduces network traffic on the main backbone network.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] If a TaskTracker fails or times out, that part of the job is rescheduled.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The TaskTracker on each node spawns a separate Java virtual machine (JVM) process to prevent the TaskTracker itself from failing if the running job crashes its JVM.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] A heartbeat is sent from the TaskTracker to the JobTracker every few minutes to check its status.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The Job Tracker and TaskTracker status and information is exposed by Jetty and can be viewed from a web browser.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] If one TaskTracker is very slow, it can delay the entire MapReduce job – especially towards the end, when everything can end up waiting for the slowest task.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] With speculative execution enabled, however, a single task can be executed on multiple slave nodes.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] By default Hadoop uses FIFO scheduling, and optionally 5 scheduling priorities to schedule jobs from a work queue.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] In version 0.19 the job scheduler was refactored out of the JobTracker, while adding the ability to use an alternate scheduler (such as the *Fair scheduler* or the *Capacity scheduler*, described next).
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler was developed by Facebook.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The goal of the fair scheduler is to provide fast response times for small jobs and quality of service (QoS) for production jobs.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler has three basic concepts.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Each pool is assigned a guaranteed minimum share.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] By default, jobs that are uncategorized go into a default pool.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Pools have to specify the minimum number of map slots, reduce slots, as well as a limit on the number of running jobs.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler was developed by Yahoo.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler supports several features that are similar to those of the fair scheduler.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Free resources are allocated to queues beyond their total capacity.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Within a queue, a job with a high level of priority has access to the queue's resources.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] There is no preemption once a job is running.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The biggest difference between Hadoop 1 and Hadoop 2 is the addition of YARN (Yet Another Resource Negotiator), which replaced the MapReduce engine in the first version of Hadoop.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] YARN strives to allocate resources to various applications effectively.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] It runs two daemons, which take care of two different tasks: the *resource manager*, which does job tracking and resource allocation to applications, the *application master*, which monitors progress of the execution.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] There are important features provided by Hadoop 3.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] For example, while there is one single *namenode* in Hadoop 2, Hadoop 3, enables having multiple name nodes, which solves the single point of failure problem.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] In Hadoop 3, there are containers working in principle of Docker, which reduces time spent on application development.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] One of the biggest changes is that Hadoop 3 decreases storage overhead with erasure coding.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Also, Hadoop 3 permits usage of GPU hardware within the cluster, which is a very substantial benefit to execute deep learning algorithms on a Hadoop cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The HDFS is not restricted to MapReduce jobs.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] It can be used for other applications, many of which are under development at Apache.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] The list includes the HBase database, the Apache Mahout machine learning system, and the Apache Hive data warehouse.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Theoretically, Hadoop could be used for any workload that is batch-oriented rather than real-time, is very data-intensive, and benefits from parallel processing.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] It can also be used to complement a real-time system, such as lambda architecture, Apache Storm, Flink, and Spark Streaming.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Inc. launched what they claimed was the world's largest Hadoop production application.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Search Webmap is a Hadoop application that runs on a Linux cluster with more than 10,000 cores and produced data that was used in every Yahoo! web search query.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] There are multiple Hadoop clusters at Yahoo! and no HDFS file systems or MapReduce jobs are split across multiple data centers.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Every Hadoop cluster node bootstraps the Linux image, including the Hadoop distribution.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Work that the clusters perform is known to include the index calculations for the Yahoo! search engine.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] In June 2009, Yahoo! made the source code of its Hadoop version available to the open-source community.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] In 2010, Facebook claimed that they had the largest Hadoop cluster in the world with 21 PB of storage.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] In June 2012, they announced the data had grown to 100 PB and later that year they announced that the data was growing by roughly half a PB per day.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] As of 2013, Hadoop adoption had become widespread: more than half of the Fortune 50 companies used Hadoop.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] Influential papers on the birth, growth, and curation of Hadoop and big data processing include: Jeffrey Dean, Sanjay Ghemawat (2004) MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters, Google.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] This paper inspired Doug Cutting to develop an open-source implementation of the Map-Reduce framework.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hadoop] He named it Hadoop, after his son's toy elephant.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hbase] HBase features compression, in-memory operation, and Bloom filters on a per-column basis as outlined in the original Bigtable paper.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hbase] Tables in HBase can serve as the input and output for MapReduce jobs run in Hadoop, and may be accessed through the Java API but also through REST, Avro or Thrift gateway APIs.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hbase] HBase is a wide-column store and has been widely adopted because of its lineage with Hadoop and HDFS.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hbase] HBase runs on top of HDFS and is well-suited for fast read and write operations on large datasets with high throughput and low input/output latency.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hbase] HBase is not a direct replacement for a classic SQL database, however Apache Phoenix project provides a SQL layer for HBase as well as JDBC driver that can be integrated with various analytics and business intelligence applications.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hbase] The Apache Trafodion project provides a SQL query engine with ODBC and JDBC drivers and distributed ACID transaction protection across multiple statements, tables and rows that use HBase as a storage engine.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hbase] HBase is now serving several data-driven websites but Facebook's Messaging Platform migrated from HBase to MyRocks in 2018.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hbase] Unlike relational and traditional databases, HBase does not support SQL scripting; instead the equivalent is written in Java, employing similarity with a MapReduce application.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hbase] In the parlance of Eric Brewer's CAP Theorem, HBase is a CP type system.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hbase] Apache HBase began as a project by the company Powerset out of a need to process massive amounts of data for the purposes of natural-language search.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hbase] Since 2010 it is a top-level Apache project.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hbase] Facebook elected to implement its new messaging platform using HBase in November 2010, but migrated away from HBase in 2018.
[src:apache-hbase/apache-hbase] The 2.5.x series is the current stable release line, it supersedes earlier release lines.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] It is now used by a number of Google applications, such as Google Analytics, web indexing, MapReduce, which is often used for generating and modifying data stored in Bigtable, Google Maps, Google Books search, "My Search History", Google Earth, Blogger.com, Google Code hosting, YouTube, and Gmail.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] Google's reasons for developing its own database include scalability and better control of performance characteristics.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] Apache HBase and Cassandra are some of the best known open source projects that were modeled after Bigtable.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] Bigtable offers HBase and Cassandra compatible APIs.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] On 6 May 2015, a public version of Bigtable was made available as a part of Google Cloud under the name Cloud Bigtable.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] As of April 2024, Bigtable manages over 10 Exabytes of data and serves more than 7 billion requests per second.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] Since its launch, Google announced a number of updates to Bigtable, including SQL support, incremental materialized views, global secondary indexes and automated scalability.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] Bigtable is one of the prototypical examples of a wide-column store.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] It maps two arbitrary string values (row key and column key) and timestamp (hence three-dimensional mapping) into an associated arbitrary byte array.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] It is not a relational database and can be better defined as a sparse, distributed multi-dimensional sorted map.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] It is built on Colossus (Google File System), Chubby Lock Service, SSTable (log-structured storage like LevelDB) and a few other Google technologies.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] Bigtable is designed to scale into the petabyte range across "hundreds or thousands of machines, and to make it easy to add more machines [to] the system and automatically start taking advantage of those resources without any reconfiguration".
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] For example, Google's copy of the web can be stored in a bigtable where the row key is a domain-reversed URL, and columns describe various properties of a web page, with one particular column holding the page itself.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] The page column can have several timestamped versions describing different copies of the web page timestamped by when they were fetched.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] Each cell of a bigtable can have zero or more timestamped versions of the data.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] Another function of the timestamp is to allow for both versioning and garbage collection of expired data.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] Tables are split into multiple *tablets* – segments of the table are split at certain row keys so that each tablet is a few hundred megabytes or a few gigabytes in size.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] A bigtable is somewhat like a mapreduce worker pool in that thousands to hundreds of thousands of tablet shards may be served by hundreds to thousands of BigTable servers.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] When Table size threaten to grow beyond a specified limit, the tablets may be compressed using the algorithm BMDiff and the Zippy compression algorithm publicly known and open-sourced as Snappy, which is a less space-optimal variation of LZ77 but more efficient in terms of computing time.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] The locations in the GFS of tablets are recorded as database entries in multiple special tablets, which are called "META1" tablets.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] META1 tablets are found by querying the single "META0" tablet, which typically resides on a server of its own since it is often queried by clients as to the location of the "META1" tablet which itself has the answer to the question of where the actual data is located.
[src:apache-hbase/bigtable] Like GFS's master server, the META0 server is not generally a bottleneck since the processor time and bandwidth necessary to discover and transmit META1 locations is minimal and clients aggressively cache locations to minimize queries.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] This is the official reference guide for the HBase version it ships with.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Herein you will find either the definitive documentation on an HBase topic as of its standing when the referenced HBase version shipped, or it will point to the location in Javadoc or JIRA where the pertinent information can be found.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] This reference guide is a work in progress.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The source for this guide can be found in the _src/main/asciidoc directory of the HBase source.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] This reference guide is marked up using AsciiDoc from which the finished guide is generated as part of the 'site' build target.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Amendments and improvements to the documentation are welcomed.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Click this link to file a new documentation bug against Apache HBase with some values pre-selected.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] For an overview of AsciiDoc and suggestions to get started contributing to the documentation, see the relevant section later in this documentation.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] If this is your first foray into the wonderful world of Distributed Computing, then you are in for some interesting times.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] First off, distributed systems are hard; making a distributed system hum requires a disparate skillset that spans systems (hardware and software) and networking.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You will also need to do a recalibration if up to this your computing has been bound to a single box.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Here is one good starting point: Fallacies of Distributed Computing.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Please use JIRA to report non-security-related bugs.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] To protect existing HBase installations from new vulnerabilities, please **do not** use JIRA to report security-related bugs.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Instead, send your report to the mailing list private@hbase.apache.org, which allows anyone to send messages, but restricts who can read them.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Someone on that list will contact you to follow up on your report.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The phrases /supported/, /not supported/, /tested/, and /not tested/ occur several places throughout this guide.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In the interest of clarity, here is a brief explanation of what is generally meant by these phrases, in the context of HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In the context of Apache HBase, /supported/ means that HBase is designed to work in the way described, and deviation from the defined behavior or functionality should be reported as a bug.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In the context of Apache HBase, /not supported/ means that a use case or use pattern is not expected to work and should be considered an antipattern.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] If you think this designation should be reconsidered for a given feature or use pattern, file a JIRA or start a discussion on one of the mailing lists.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In the context of Apache HBase, /tested/ means that a feature is covered by unit or integration tests, and has been proven to work as expected.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In the context of Apache HBase, /not tested/ means that a feature or use pattern may or may not work in a given way, and may or may not corrupt your data or cause operational issues.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] It is an unknown, and there are no guarantees.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] If you can provide proof that a feature designated as /not tested/ does work in a given way, please submit the tests and/or the metrics so that other users can gain certainty about such features or use patterns.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Quickstart will get you up and running on a single-node, standalone instance of HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] This section describes the setup of a single-node standalone HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] A *standalone* instance has all HBase daemons — the Master, RegionServers, and ZooKeeper — running in a single JVM persisting to the local filesystem.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] We will show you how to create a table in HBase using the `hbase shell` CLI, insert rows into the table, perform put and scan operations against the table, enable or disable the table, and start and stop HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Apart from downloading HBase, this procedure should take less than 10 minutes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] See Java for information about supported JDK versions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Extract the downloaded file, and change to the newly-created directory.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You must set the `JAVA_HOME` environment variable before starting HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] To make this easier, HBase lets you set it within the *conf/hbase-env.sh* file.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You must locate where Java is installed on your machine, and one way to find this is by using the *whereis java* command.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Once you have the location, edit the *conf/hbase-env.sh* file and uncomment the line starting with *#export JAVA_HOME=*, and then set it to your Java installation path.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The *bin/start-hbase.sh* script is provided as a convenient way to start HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Issue the command, and if all goes well, a message is logged to standard output showing that HBase started successfully.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can use the `jps` command to verify that you have one running process called `HMaster`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In standalone mode HBase runs all daemons within this single JVM, i.e. the HMaster, a single HRegionServer, and the ZooKeeper daemon.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Go to *http://localhost:16010* to view the HBase Web UI.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Type `help` and press Enter, to display some basic usage information for HBase Shell, as well as several example commands.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Notice that table names, rows, columns all must be enclosed in quote characters.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Use the `create` command to create a new table.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You must specify the table name and the ColumnFamily name.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] To put data into your table, use the `put` command.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The first insert is at `row1`, column `cf:a`, with a value of `value1`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Columns in HBase are comprised of a column family prefix, `cf` in this example, followed by a colon and then a column qualifier suffix, `a` in this case.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] One of the ways to get data from HBase is to scan.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Use the `scan` command to scan the table for data.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can limit your scan, but for now, all data is fetched.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] To get a single row of data at a time, use the `get` command.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] If you want to delete a table or change its settings, as well as in some other situations, you need to disable the table first, using the `disable` command.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can re-enable it using the `enable` command.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] To drop (delete) a table, use the `drop` command.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] To exit the HBase Shell and disconnect from your cluster, use the `quit` command.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] HBase is still running in the background.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] After issuing the command, it can take several minutes for the processes to shut down.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Use the `jps` to be sure that the HMaster and HRegionServer processes are shut down.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The above has shown you how to start and stop a standalone instance of HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In the next sections we give a quick overview of other modes of hbase deploy.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] After working your way through quickstart standalone mode, you can re-configure HBase to run in pseudo-distributed mode.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Pseudo-distributed mode means that HBase still runs completely on a single host, but each HBase daemon (HMaster, HRegionServer, and ZooKeeper) runs as a separate process: in standalone mode all daemons ran in one jvm process/instance.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] By default, unless you configure the `hbase.rootdir` property as described in quickstart, your data is still stored in */tmp/*.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In this walk-through, we store your data in HDFS instead, assuming you have HDFS available.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can skip the HDFS configuration to continue storing your data in the local filesystem.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Edit the *hbase-site.xml* configuration.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] First, add the following property which directs HBase to run in distributed mode, with one JVM instance per daemon.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] `<property> <name>hbase.cluster.distributed</name> <value>true</value> </property>` Next, add a configuration for `hbase.rootdir`, pointing to the address of your HDFS instance, using the `hdfs:////` URI syntax.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In this example, HDFS is running on the localhost at port 8020.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] `<property> <name>hbase.rootdir</name> <value>hdfs://localhost:9000/hbase</value> </property>` You do not need to create the directory in HDFS.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] If you create the directory, HBase will attempt to do a migration, which is not what you want.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Use the *bin/start-hbase.sh* command to start HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] If your system is configured correctly, the `jps` command should show the HMaster and HRegionServer processes running.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] If everything worked correctly, HBase created its directory in HDFS.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In the configuration above, it is stored in */hbase/* on HDFS.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can use the `hadoop fs` command in Hadoop’s *bin/* directory to list this directory.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Create a table and populate it with data.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can use the HBase Shell to create a table, populate it with data, scan and get values from it, using the same procedure as in shell exercises.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Start and stop a backup HBase Master (HMaster) server.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Running multiple HMaster instances on the same hardware does not make sense in a production environment, in the same way that running a pseudo-distributed cluster does not make sense for production.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] This step is offered for testing and learning purposes only.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The HMaster server controls the HBase cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can start up to 9 backup HMaster servers, which makes 10 total HMasters, counting the primary.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] To start a backup HMaster, use the `local-master-backup.sh`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] For each backup master you want to start, add a parameter representing the port offset for that master.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Each HMaster uses two ports (16000 and 16010 by default).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The port offset is added to these ports, so using an offset of 2, the backup HMaster would use ports 16002 and 16012.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] `$ ./bin/local-master-backup.sh start 2 3 5` To kill a backup master without killing the entire cluster, you need to find its process ID (PID).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The PID is stored in a file with a name like */tmp/hbase-USER-X-master.pid*.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The only contents of the file is the PID.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can use the `kill -9` command to kill that PID.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Start and stop additional RegionServers The HRegionServer manages the data in its StoreFiles as directed by the HMaster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Generally, one HRegionServer runs per node in the cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Running multiple HRegionServers on the same system can be useful for testing in pseudo-distributed mode.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The `local-regionservers.sh` command allows you to run multiple RegionServers.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] It works in a similar way to the `local-master-backup.sh` command, in that each parameter you provide represents the port offset for an instance.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Each RegionServer requires two ports, and the default ports are 16020 and 16030.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Since HBase version 1.1.0, HMaster doesn’t use region server ports, this leaves 10 ports (16020 to 16029 and 16030 to 16039) to be used for RegionServers.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] For supporting additional RegionServers, set environment variables HBASE_RS_BASE_PORT and HBASE_RS_INFO_BASE_PORT to appropriate values before running script `local-regionservers.sh`. e.g.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] With values 16200 and 16300 for base ports, 99 additional RegionServers can be supported, on a server.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The following command starts four additional RegionServers, running on sequential ports starting at 16022/16032 (base ports 16020/16030 plus 2).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] `$ ./bin/local-regionservers.sh start 2 3 4 5` To stop a RegionServer manually, use the `local-regionservers.sh` command with the `stop` parameter and the offset of the server to stop.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can stop HBase the same way as in the quickstart procedure, using the *bin/stop-hbase.sh* command.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In reality, you need a fully-distributed configuration to fully test HBase and to use it in real-world scenarios.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In a distributed configuration, the cluster contains multiple nodes, each of which runs one or more HBase daemon.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] These include primary and backup Master instances, multiple ZooKeeper nodes, and multiple RegionServer nodes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] This advanced quickstart adds two more nodes to your cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] This quickstart assumes that each node is a virtual machine and that they are all on the same network.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] It builds upon the previous quickstart, Pseudo-Distributed for Local Testing, assuming that the system you configured in that procedure is now `node-a`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Stop HBase on `node-a` before continuing.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] `node-a` needs to be able to log into `node-b` and `node-c` (and to itself) in order to start the daemons.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The easiest way to accomplish this is to use the same username on all hosts, and configure password-less SSH login from `node-a` to each of the others.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Create the directory that will hold the shared keys on the other nodes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] On `node-b` and `node-c`, log in as the HBase user and create a *.ssh/* directory in the user’s home directory, if it does not already exist.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] If it already exists, be aware that it may already contain other keys.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Securely copy the public key from `node-a` to each of the nodes, by using the `scp` or some other secure means.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] On each of the other nodes, create a new file called *.ssh/authorized_keys* *if it does not already exist*, and append the contents of the *id_rsa.pub* file to the end of it.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Note that you also need to do this for `node-a` itself.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] If you performed the procedure correctly, you should not be prompted for a password when you SSH from `node-a` to either of the other nodes using the same username.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Since `node-b` will run a backup Master, repeat the procedure above, substituting `node-b` everywhere you see `node-a`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Be sure not to overwrite your existing *.ssh/authorized_keys* files, but concatenate the new key onto the existing file using the `>>` operator rather than the `>` operator.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] `node-a` will run your primary master and ZooKeeper processes, but no RegionServers.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Stop the RegionServer from starting on `node-a`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Configure HBase to use `node-b` as a backup master.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Create a new file in *conf/* called *backup-masters*, and add a new line to it with the hostname for `node-b`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In this demonstration, the hostname is `node-b.example.com`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Configure ZooKeeper In reality, you should carefully consider your ZooKeeper configuration.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can find out more about configuring ZooKeeper in zookeeper section.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] This configuration will direct HBase to start and manage a ZooKeeper instance on each node of the cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] On `node-a`, edit *conf/hbase-site.xml* and add the following properties.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Everywhere in your configuration that you have referred to `node-a` as `localhost`, change the reference to point to the hostname that the other nodes will use to refer to `node-a`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In these examples, the hostname is `node-a.example.com`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] `node-b` will run a backup master server and a ZooKeeper instance.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Copy the configuration files from `node-a` to `node-b`.and `node-c`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Each node of your cluster needs to have the same configuration information.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Copy the contents of the *conf/* directory to the *conf/* directory on `node-b` and `node-c`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] On `node-a`, issue the `start-hbase.sh` command.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Your output will be similar to that below.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] On each node of the cluster, run the `jps` command and verify that the correct processes are running on each server.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You may see additional Java processes running on your servers as well, if they are used for other purposes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] If you use ZooKeeper this way, it is limited to one instance per cluster node and is appropriate for testing only.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] If ZooKeeper is run outside of HBase, the process is called `QuorumPeer`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] For more about ZooKeeper configuration, including using an external ZooKeeper instance with HBase, see zookeeper section.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] If everything is set up correctly, you should be able to connect to the UI for the Master `http://node-a.example.com:16010/` or the secondary master at `http://node-b.example.com:16010/` using a web browser.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] If you can connect via `localhost` but not from another host, check your firewall rules.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can see the web UI for each of the RegionServers at port 16030 of their IP addresses, or by clicking their links in the web UI for the Master.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Test what happens when nodes or services disappear.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] With a three-node cluster you have configured, things will not be very resilient.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can still test the behavior of the primary Master or a RegionServer by killing the associated processes and watching the logs.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The next chapter, configuration, gives more information about the different HBase run modes, system requirements for running HBase, and critical configuration areas for setting up a distributed HBase cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] chapter to further explain configuration of Apache HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] to ensure that your HBase testing and deployment goes smoothly.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Apache HBase uses the same configuration system as Apache Hadoop.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] All configuration files are located in the *conf/* directory, which needs to be kept in sync for each node on your cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] A plain-text file which lists hosts on which the Master should start a backup Master process, one host per line.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Used to connect HBase Hadoop’s Metrics2 framework.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] See the Hadoop Wiki entry for more information on Metrics2.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Contains only commented-out examples by default.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Script for Windows and Linux / Unix environments to set up the working environment for HBase, including the location of Java, Java options, and other environment variables.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The file contains many commented-out examples to provide guidance.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The default policy configuration file used by RPC servers to make authorization decisions on client requests.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] This file specifies configuration options which override HBase’s default configuration.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can view (but do not edit) the default configuration file at *hbase-common/src/main/resources/hbase-default.xml*.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can also view the entire effective configuration for your cluster (defaults and overrides) in the HBase Configuration tab of the HBase Web UI.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Configuration file for HBase logging via `log4j2`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] A plain-text file containing a list of hosts which should run a RegionServer in your HBase cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] By default, this file contains the single entry `localhost`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] It should contain a list of hostnames or IP addresses, one per line, and should only contain `localhost` if each node in your cluster will run a RegionServer on its `localhost` interface.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] This section lists required services and some required system configuration.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] HBase runs on the Java Virtual Machine, thus all HBase deployments require a JVM runtime.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The following table summarizes the recommendations of the HBase community with respect to running on various Java versions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The symbol indicates a base level of testing and willingness to help diagnose and address issues you might run into; these are the expected deployment combinations.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] An entry of means that there may be challenges with this combination, and you should look for more information before deciding to pursue this as your deployment strategy.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The means this combination does not work; either an older Java version is considered deprecated by the HBase community, or this combination is known to not work.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] For combinations of newer JDK with older HBase releases, it’s likely there are known compatibility issues that cannot be addressed under our compatibility guarantees, making the combination impossible.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In some cases, specific guidance on limitations (e.g. whether compiling / unit tests work, specific operational issues, etc) are also noted.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Assume any combination not listed here is considered .
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] HBase uses the Secure Shell (ssh) command and utilities extensively to communicate between cluster nodes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Each server in the cluster must be running `ssh` so that the Hadoop and HBase daemons can be managed.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You must be able to connect to all nodes via SSH, including the local node, from the Master as well as any backup Master, using a shared key rather than a password.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can see the basic methodology for such a set-up in Linux or Unix systems at "Procedure: Configure Passwordless SSH Access".
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] If your cluster nodes use OS X, see the section, SSH: Setting up Remote Desktop and Enabling Self-Login on the Hadoop wiki.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] HBase uses the local hostname to self-report its IP address.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The clocks on cluster nodes should be synchronized.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] A small amount of variation is acceptable, but larger amounts of skew can cause erratic and unexpected behavior.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Time synchronization is one of the first things to check if you see unexplained problems in your cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] It is recommended that you run a Network Time Protocol (NTP) service, or another time-synchronization mechanism on your cluster and that all nodes look to the same service for time synchronization.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] See the Basic NTP Configuration at *The Linux Documentation Project (TLDP)* to set up NTP.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] It requires the ability to open a large number of files at once.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Many Linux distributions limit the number of files a single user is allowed to open to `1024` (or `256` on older versions of OS X).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can check this limit on your servers by running the command `ulimit -n` when logged in as the user which runs HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] See the Troubleshooting section for some of the problems you may experience if the limit is too low.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] It is recommended to raise the ulimit to at least 10,000, but more likely 10,240, because the value is usually expressed in multiples of 1024.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Each ColumnFamily has at least one StoreFile, and possibly more than six StoreFiles if the region is under load.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The number of open files required depends upon the number of ColumnFamilies and the number of regions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The following is a rough formula for calculating the potential number of open files on a RegionServer.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] For example, assuming that a schema had 3 ColumnFamilies per region with an average of 3 StoreFiles per ColumnFamily, and there are 100 regions per RegionServer, the JVM will open `3 * 3 * 100 = 900` file descriptors, not counting open JAR files, configuration files, and others.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Opening a file does not take many resources, and the risk of allowing a user to open too many files is minimal.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Another related setting is the number of processes a user is allowed to run at once.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In Linux and Unix, the number of processes is set using the `ulimit -u` command.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] This should not be confused with the `nproc` command, which controls the number of CPUs available to a given user.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Under load, a `ulimit -u` that is too low can cause OutOfMemoryError exceptions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Configuring the maximum number of file descriptors and processes for the user who is running the HBase process is an operating system configuration, rather than an HBase configuration.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] It is also important to be sure that the settings are changed for the user that actually runs HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] To see which user started HBase, and that user’s ulimit configuration, look at the first line of the HBase log for that instance.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] To configure ulimit settings on Ubuntu, edit */etc/security/limits.conf*, which is a space-delimited file with four columns.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Refer to the man page for *limits.conf* for details about the format of this file.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] In the following example, the first line sets both soft and hard limits for the number of open files (nofile) to 32768 for the operating system user with the username hadoop.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The second line sets the number of processes to 32000 for the same user.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The settings are only applied if the Pluggable Authentication Module (PAM) environment is directed to use them.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] All of the shell scripts that come with HBase rely on the GNU Bash shell.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Running production systems on Windows machines is not recommended.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The following table summarizes the versions of Hadoop supported with each version of HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Older versions not appearing in this table are considered unsupported and likely missing necessary features, while newer versions are untested but may be suitable.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Based on the version of HBase, you should select the most appropriate version of Hadoop.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] You can use Apache Hadoop, or a vendor’s distribution of Hadoop.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] See the Hadoop wiki for information about vendors of Hadoop.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] For HBase 2.5.1 and earlier, the official HBase binary releases and Maven artifacts were built with Hadoop 2.x.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Starting with HBase 2.5.2, HBase provides binary releases and Maven artifacts built with both Hadoop 2.x and Hadoop 3.x.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The Hadoop 2 artifacts do not have any version suffix, the Hadoop 3 artifacts add the `-hadoop-3` suffix to the version. i.e.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] `hbase-2.5.2-bin.tar.gz.asc` is the Binary release built with Hadoop2, and `hbase-2.5.2-hadoop3-bin.tar.gz` is the release built with Hadoop 3.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Each HBase release has a default Hadoop 3 version.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] This is used when the Hadoop 3 version is not specified during build, and for building the official binary releases and artifacts.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Generally when a new minor version is released (i.e.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] 2.5.0) the default version is set to the latest supported Hadoop 3 version at the start of the release process.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Up to HBase 2.5.10 and 2.6.1 even if HBase added support for newer Hadoop 3 releases in a patch release, the default Hadoop 3 version (and the one used in the official binary releases) was not updated.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] This simplified upgrading, but meant that HBase releases often included old unfixed CVEs both from Hadoop and Hadoop’s dependencies, even when newer Hadoop releases with fixes were available.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Starting with HBase 2.5.11 and 2.6.2, the default Hadoop 3 version is always set to the latest supported Hadoop 3 version, and is also used for the `-hadoop3` binary releases and artifacts.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] This will drastically reduce the number of known CVEs shipped in the HBase binary releases, and make sure that all fixes and improvements in Hadoop are included.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] An HDFS DataNode has an upper bound on the number of files that it will serve at any one time.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Be sure to restart your HDFS after making the above configuration.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] Not having this configuration in place makes for strange-looking failures.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] One manifestation is a complaint about missing blocks.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] See also casestudies.max.transfer.threads and note that this property was previously known as `dfs.datanode.max.xcievers` (e.g.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p01] The exact version depends on your version of HBase, though the minimum ZooKeeper version is 3.4.x due to the `useMulti` feature made default in 1.0.0 (see HBASE-16598).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] HBase has two run modes: standalone and distributed.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Out of the box, HBase runs in standalone mode.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Whatever your mode, you will need to configure HBase by editing files in the HBase *conf* directory.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] At a minimum, you must edit conf/hbase-env.sh to tell HBase which java to use.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] In this file you set HBase environment variables such as the heapsize and other options for the `JVM`, the preferred location for log files, etc.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Set JAVA_HOME to point at the root of your java install.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Standalone mode is what is described in the quickstart section.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] In standalone mode, HBase does not use HDFS — it uses the local filesystem instead — and it runs all HBase daemons and a local ZooKeeper all up in the same JVM.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] ZooKeeper binds to a well-known port so clients may talk to HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] A sometimes useful variation on standalone hbase has all daemons running inside the one JVM but rather than persist to the local filesystem, instead they persist to an HDFS instance.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] You might consider this profile when you are intent on a simple deploy profile, the loading is light, but the data must persist across node comings and goings.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Writing to HDFS where data is replicated ensures the latter.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] To configure this standalone variant, edit your *hbase-site.xml* setting *hbase.rootdir* to point at a directory in your HDFS instance but then set *hbase.cluster.distributed* to *false*.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Distributed mode can be subdivided into distributed but all daemons run on a single node — a.k.a.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] *pseudo-distributed* — and *fully-distributed* where the daemons are spread across all nodes in the cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] *fully-distributed* nomenclature comes from Hadoop.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Pseudo-distributed mode can run against the local filesystem or it can run against an instance of the *Hadoop Distributed File System* (HDFS).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Fully-distributed mode can ONLY run on HDFS.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] See the Hadoop documentation for how to set up HDFS.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] A good walk-through for setting up HDFS on Hadoop 2 can be found at https://web.archive.org/web/20221007121526/https://www.alexjf.net/blog/distributed-systems/hadoop-yarn-installation-definitive-guide/.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] A pseudo-distributed mode is simply a fully-distributed mode run on a single host.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Use this HBase configuration for testing and prototyping purposes only.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Do not use this configuration for production or for performance evaluation.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] By default, HBase runs in stand-alone mode.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Both stand-alone mode and pseudo-distributed mode are provided for the purposes of small-scale testing.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] For a production environment, distributed mode is advised.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] In distributed mode, multiple instances of HBase daemons run on multiple servers in the cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Just as in pseudo-distributed mode, a fully distributed configuration requires that you set the `hbase.cluster.distributed` property to `true`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Typically, the `hbase.rootdir` is configured to point to a highly-available HDFS filesystem.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] In addition, the cluster is configured so that multiple cluster nodes enlist as RegionServers, ZooKeeper QuorumPeers, and backup HMaster servers.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] These configuration basics are all demonstrated in quickstart-fully-distributed.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Typically, your cluster will contain multiple RegionServers all running on different servers, as well as primary and backup Master and ZooKeeper daemons.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] The *conf/regionservers* file on the master server contains a list of hosts whose RegionServers are associated with this cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] All hosts listed in this file will have their RegionServer processes started and stopped when the master server starts or stops.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] See the ZooKeeper section for ZooKeeper setup instructions for HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] This is a bare-bones *conf/hbase-site.xml* for a distributed HBase cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] A cluster that is used for real-world work would contain more custom configuration parameters.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Most HBase configuration directives have default values, which are used unless the value is overridden in the *hbase-site.xml*.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] See "Configuration Files" for more information.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] This is an example *conf/regionservers* file, which contains a list of nodes that should run a RegionServer in the cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] These nodes need HBase installed and they need to use the same contents of the *conf/* directory as the Master server.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] This is an example *conf/backup-masters* file, which contains a list of each node that should run a backup Master instance.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] The backup Master instances will sit idle unless the main Master becomes unavailable.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] See quickstart-fully-distributed for a walk-through of a simple three-node cluster configuration with multiple ZooKeeper, backup HMaster, and RegionServer instances.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] An example of such an HDFS client configuration is `dfs.replication`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] If for example, you want to run with a replication factor of 5, HBase will create files with the default of 3 unless you do the above to make the configuration available to HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Starting with HBase 3.0, HBase includes two binary packages.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] The classic package includes both the HBase and Hadoop components, while the Hadoop-less "Bring Your Own Hadoop" package omits the Hadoop components, and uses the files from an existing Hadoop installation.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] The classic binary package filename is named `hbase-<version>-bin.tar.gz` i.e.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] *hbase-3.0.0-bin.tar.gz* , while the Hadoop-less package is `hbase-byo-hadoop-<version>-bin.tar.gz` i.e.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] If the cluster nodes already have Hadoop installed, you can use the Hadoop-less package.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] In this case you need to make sure that the `HADOOP_HOME` environment variable is set and points to the Hadoop installation.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] The easiest way to ensure this is to set it in *hbase-env.sh*.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] You still need to make sure that the Hadoop configuration files are present on the HBase classpath, as described above.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Start and stop the Hadoop HDFS daemons by running *bin/start-hdfs.sh* over in the `HADOOP_HOME` directory.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] You can ensure it started properly by testing the `put` and `get` of files into the Hadoop filesystem.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] HBase does not normally use the MapReduce or YARN daemons.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Run the above from the `HBASE_HOME` directory.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] You should now have a running HBase instance.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] HBase logs can be found in the *logs* subdirectory.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Check them out especially if HBase had trouble starting.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] HBase also puts up a UI listing vital attributes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] By default it’s deployed on the Master host at port 16010 (HBase RegionServers listen on port 16020 by default and put up an informational HTTP server at port 16030).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] If the Master is running on a host named `master.example.org` on the default port, point your browser at http://master.example.org:16010 to see the web interface.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] Once HBase has started, see the shell exercises section for how to create tables, add data, scan your insertions, and finally disable and drop your tables.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] It can take longer if your cluster is comprised of many machines.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p02] If you are running a distributed operation, be sure to wait until HBase has shut down completely before stopping the Hadoop daemons.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Just as in Hadoop where you add site-specific HDFS configuration to the *hdfs-site.xml* file, for HBase, site specific customizations go into the file *conf/hbase-site.xml*.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] For the list of configurable properties, see hbase default configurations below or view the raw *hbase-default.xml* source file in the HBase source code at *src/main/resources*.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Not all configuration options make it out to *hbase-default.xml*.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Some configurations would only appear in source code; the only way to identify these changes are through code review.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Currently, changes here will require a cluster restart for HBase to notice the change.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The documentation below is generated using the default hbase configuration file, *hbase-default.xml*, as source.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Temporary directory on the local filesystem.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Change this setting to point to a location more permanent than '/tmp', the usual resolve for java.io.tmpdir, as the '/tmp' directory is cleared on machine restart.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The directory shared by region servers and into which HBase persists.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The URL should be 'fully-qualified' to include the filesystem scheme.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] For example, to specify the HDFS directory '/hbase' where the HDFS instance’s namenode is running at namenode.example.org on port 9000, set this value to: hdfs://namenode.example.org:9000/hbase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] By default, we write to whatever ${hbase.tmp.dir} is set too — usually /tmp — so change this configuration or else all data will be lost on machine restart.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Possible values are false for standalone mode and true for distributed mode.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If false, startup will run all HBase and ZooKeeper daemons together in the one JVM.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Comma separated list of servers in the ZooKeeper ensemble (This config. should have been named hbase.zookeeper.ensemble).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] For example, "host1.mydomain.com,host2.mydomain.com,host3.mydomain.com".
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] By default this is set to localhost for local and pseudo-distributed modes of operation.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] For a fully-distributed setup, this should be set to a full list of ZooKeeper ensemble servers.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If HBASE_MANAGES_ZK is set in hbase-env.sh this is the list of servers which hbase will start/stop ZooKeeper on as part of cluster start/stop.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Client-side, we will take this list of ensemble members and put it together with the hbase.zookeeper.property.clientPort config. and pass it into zookeeper constructor as the connectString parameter.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Directory on the local filesystem to be used as a local storage.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The port the HBase Master should bind to.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Set to -1 if you do not want a UI instance run.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A comma-separated list of BaseLogCleanerDelegate invoked by the LogsCleaner service.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] These WAL cleaners are called in order, so put the cleaner that prunes the most files in front.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] To implement your own BaseLogCleanerDelegate, just put it in HBase’s classpath and add the fully qualified class name here.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Always add the above default log cleaners in the list.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] How long a WAL remain in the archive ({hbase.rootdir}/oldWALs) directory, after which it will be cleaned by a Master thread.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A comma-separated list of BaseHFileCleanerDelegate invoked by the HFileCleaner service.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] These HFiles cleaners are called in order, so put the cleaner that prunes the most files in front.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] To implement your own BaseHFileCleanerDelegate, just put it in HBase’s classpath and add the fully qualified class name here.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Always add the above default hfile cleaners in the list as they will be overwritten in hbase-site.xml.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Whether or not the Master listens to the Master web UI port (hbase.master.info.port) and redirects requests to the web UI server shared by the Master and RegionServer.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Config. makes sense when Master is serving Regions (not the default).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Splitting a region, how long to wait on the file-splitting step before aborting the attempt.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] This setting used to be known as hbase.regionserver.fileSplitTimeout in hbase-1.x.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Split is now run master-side hence the rename (If a 'hbase.master.fileSplitTimeout' setting found, will use it to prime the current 'hbase.master.fileSplitTimeout' Configuration.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The port the HBase RegionServer binds to.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The port for the HBase RegionServer web UI Set to -1 if you do not want the RegionServer UI to run.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Whether or not the Master or RegionServer UI should search for a port to bind to.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Enables automatic port search if hbase.regionserver.info.port is already in use.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Useful for testing, turned off by default.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Count of RPC Listener instances spun up on RegionServers.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Same property is used by the Master for count of master handlers.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Too many handlers can be counter-productive.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If mostly read-only, handlers count close to cpu count does well.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Start with twice the CPU count and tune from there.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Factor to determine the number of call queues.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A value of 0 means a single queue shared between all the handlers.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A value of 1 means that each handler has its own queue.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Split the call queues into read and write queues.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The specified interval (which should be between 0.0 and 1.0) will be multiplied by the number of call queues.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A value of 0 indicate to not split the call queues, meaning that both read and write requests will be pushed to the same set of queues.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A value lower than 0.5 means that there will be less read queues than write queues.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A value of 0.5 means there will be the same number of read and write queues.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A value greater than 0.5 means that there will be more read queues than write queues.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A value of 1.0 means that all the queues except one are used to dispatch read requests.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Given the number of read call queues, calculated from the total number of call queues multiplied by the callqueue.read.ratio, the scan.ratio property will split the read call queues into small-read and long-read queues.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A value lower than 0.5 means that there will be less long-read queues than short-read queues.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A value of 0.5 means that there will be the same number of short-read and long-read queues.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A value greater than 0.5 means that there will be more long-read queues than short-read queues A value of 0 or 1 indicate to use the same set of queues for gets and scans.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Interval between messages from the RegionServer to Master in milliseconds.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Period at which we will roll the commit log regardless of how many edits it has.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The number of consecutive WAL close errors we will allow before triggering a server abort.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A setting of 0 will cause the region server to abort if closing the current WAL writer fails during log rolling.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Even a small value (2 or 3) will allow a region server to ride over transient HDFS errors.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Defines the minimum amount of heap memory that must remain free for the RegionServer to start, specified in bytes or human-readable formats like '512m' for megabytes or '4g' for gigabytes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If not set, the default is 20% of the total heap size.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] To disable the check entirely, set this value to 0.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If the combined memory usage of memstore and block cache exceeds (total heap - this value), the RegionServer will fail to start.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Maximum size of all memstores in a region server before new updates are blocked and flushes are forced.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Updates are blocked and flushes are forced until size of all memstores in a region server hits hbase.regionserver.global.memstore.size.lower.limit.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The default value in this configuration has been intentionally left empty in order to honor the old hbase.regionserver.global.memstore.upperLimit property if present.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Maximum size of all memstores in a region server before flushes are forced.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Defaults to 95% of hbase.regionserver.global.memstore.size (0.95).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A 100% value for this value causes the minimum possible flushing to occur when updates are blocked due to memstore limiting.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The default value in this configuration has been intentionally left empty in order to honor the old hbase.regionserver.global.memstore.lowerLimit property if present.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Determines the type of memstore to be used for system tables like META, namespace tables etc.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] By default NONE is the type and hence we use the default memstore for all the system tables.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Maximum amount of time an edit lives in memory before being automatically flushed.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Set it to 0 to disable automatic flushing.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The name of the Network Interface from which a region server should report its IP address.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The host name or IP address of the name server (DNS) which a region server should use to determine the host name used by the master for communication and display purposes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A split policy determines when a region should be split.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The various other split policies that are available currently are BusyRegionSplitPolicy, ConstantSizeRegionSplitPolicy, DisabledRegionSplitPolicy, DelimitedKeyPrefixRegionSplitPolicy, KeyPrefixRegionSplitPolicy, and SteppingSplitPolicy.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] DisabledRegionSplitPolicy blocks manual region splitting.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Limit for the number of regions after which no more region splitting should take place.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] This is not hard limit for the number of regions but acts as a guideline for the regionserver to stop splitting after a certain limit.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] ZooKeeper session timeout in milliseconds.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] First, this value is used in the ZK client that HBase uses to connect to the ensemble.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] It is also used by HBase when it starts a ZK server and it is passed as the 'maxSessionTimeout'.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] See https://zookeeper.apache.org/doc/current/zookeeperProgrammers.html#ch_zkSessions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] For example, if an HBase region server connects to a ZK ensemble that’s also managed by HBase, then the session timeout will be the one specified by this configuration.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] But, a region server that connects to an ensemble managed with a different configuration will be subjected that ensemble’s maxSessionTimeout.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] So, even though HBase might propose using 90 seconds, the ensemble can have a max timeout lower than this and it will take precedence.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The current default maxSessionTimeout that ZK ships with is 40 seconds, which is lower than HBase’s.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] All of HBase’s ZooKeeper files that are configured with a relative path will go under this node.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] By default, all of HBase’s ZooKeeper file paths are configured with a relative path, so they will all go under this directory unless changed.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The name of the Network Interface from which a ZooKeeper server should report its IP address.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The host name or IP address of the name server (DNS) which a ZooKeeper server should use to determine the host name used by the master for communication and display purposes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Port used by ZooKeeper peers to talk to each other.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] See https://zookeeper.apache.org/doc/r3.4.10/zookeeperStarted.html#sc_RunningReplicatedZooKeeper for more information.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Port used by ZooKeeper for leader election.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Property from ZooKeeper’s config zoo.cfg.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The number of ticks that the initial synchronization phase can take.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The number of ticks that can pass between sending a request and getting an acknowledgment.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The directory where the snapshot is stored.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The port at which the clients will connect.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Limit on number of concurrent connections (at the socket level) that a single client, identified by IP address, may make to a single member of the ZooKeeper ensemble.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Set high to avoid zk connection issues running standalone and pseudo-distributed.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Default size of the BufferedMutator write buffer in bytes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A bigger buffer takes more memory — on both the client and server side since server instantiates the passed write buffer to process it — but a larger buffer size reduces the number of RPCs made.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Used mostly as value to wait before running a retry of a failed get, region lookup, etc.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] See hbase.client.retries.number for description of how we backoff from this initial pause amount and how this pause works w/ retries.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Pause time when encountering an exception indicating a server is overloaded, CallQueueTooBigException or CallDroppedException.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Set this property to a higher value than hbase.client.pause if you observe frequent CallQueueTooBigException or CallDroppedException from the same RegionServer and the call queue there keeps filling up.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] This config used to be called hbase.client.pause.cqtbe, which has been deprecated as of 2.5.0.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Used as maximum for all retryable operations such as the getting of a cell’s value, starting a row update, etc.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Retry interval is a rough function based on hbase.client.pause.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] At first we retry at this interval but then with backoff, we pretty quickly reach retrying every ten seconds.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] See HConstants#RETRY_BACKOFF for how the backup ramps up.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Change this setting and hbase.client.pause to suit your workload.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The maximum number of concurrent mutation tasks a single HTable instance will send to the cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The maximum number of concurrent mutation tasks a single HTable instance will send to a single region server.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The maximum number of concurrent mutation tasks the client will maintain to a single Region.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] That is, if there is already hbase.client.max.perregion.tasks writes in progress for this region, new puts won’t be sent to this region until some writes finishes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The max number of concurrent pending requests for one server in all client threads (process level).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Exceeding requests will be thrown ServerTooBusyException immediately to prevent user’s threads being occupied and blocked by only one slow region server.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If you use a fix number of threads to access HBase in a synchronous way, set this to a suitable value which is related to the number of threads will help you.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] See https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-16388 for details.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Number of rows that we try to fetch when calling next on a scanner if it is not served from (local, client) memory.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] This configuration works together with hbase.client.scanner.max.result.size to try and use the network efficiently.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The default value is Integer.MAX_VALUE by default so that the network will fill the chunk size defined by hbase.client.scanner.max.result.size rather than be limited by a particular number of rows since the size of rows varies table to table.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If you know ahead of time that you will not require more than a certain number of rows from a scan, this configuration should be set to that row limit via Scan#setCaching.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Higher caching values will enable faster scanners but will eat up more memory and some calls of next may take longer and longer times when the cache is empty.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Specifies the combined maximum allowed size of a KeyValue instance.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] This is to set an upper boundary for a single entry saved in a storage file.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Since they cannot be split it helps avoiding that a region cannot be split any further because the data is too large.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] It seems wise to set this to a fraction of the maximum region size.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Setting it to zero or less disables the check.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Maximum allowed size of an individual cell, inclusive of value and all key components.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A value of 0 or less disables the check.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] This is a safety setting to protect the server from OOM situations.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Client scanner lease period in milliseconds.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] This is maximum number of iterations to atomic bulk loads are attempted in the face of splitting operations 0 means never give up.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Request Compaction after bulkload immediately.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If bulkload is continuous, the triggered compactions may increase load, bring about performance side effect.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The max percent of regions in transition when balancing.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If set this config to 0.01, It means that there are at most 1% regions in transition when balancing.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Then the cluster’s availability is at least 99% when balancing.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Period at which the region balancer runs in the Master, in milliseconds.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Period at which the oldWALs directory size calculator/updater will run in the Master, in milliseconds.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The load balancer can trigger for several reasons.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] This value controls one of those reasons.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Run the balancer if any regionserver has a region count outside the range of average +/- (average * slop) regions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If the value of slop is negative, disable sloppiness checks.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The balancer can still run for other reasons, but sloppiness will not be one of them.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If the value of slop is 0, run the balancer if any server has a region count more than 1 from the average.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If the value of slop is 100, run the balancer if any server has a region count greater than 101 times the average.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The default value of this parameter is 0.2, which runs the balancer if any server has a region count less than 80% of the average, or greater than 120% of the average.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Note that for the default StochasticLoadBalancer, this does not guarantee any balancing actions will be taken, but only that the balancer will attempt to run.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Period at which the region normalizer runs in the Master, in milliseconds.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Whether to split a region as part of normalization.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Whether to merge a region as part of normalization.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The minimum number of regions in a table to consider it for merge normalization.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The minimum age for a region to be considered for a merge, in days.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The minimum size for a region to be considered for a merge, in whole MBs.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The maximum number of region count in a merge request for merge normalization.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] This config is used to set default behaviour of normalizer at table level.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] In master side, this config is the period used for FS related behaviors: checking if hdfs is out of safe mode, setting or checking hbase.version file, setting or checking hbase.id file.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] In regionserver side, this config is used in several places: flushing check interval, compaction check interval, wal rolling check interval.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Specially, admin can tune flushing and compaction check interval by hbase.regionserver.flush.check.period and hbase.regionserver.compaction.check.period.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] It determines the flushing check period of PeriodicFlusher in regionserver.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If unset, it uses hbase.server.thread.wakefrequency as default value.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] It determines the compaction check period of CompactionChecker in regionserver.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] How many times to retry attempting to write a version file before just aborting.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Each attempt is separated by the hbase.server.thread.wakefrequency milliseconds.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Memstore will be flushed to disk if size of the memstore exceeds this number of bytes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Value is checked by a thread that runs every hbase.server.thread.wakefrequency.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If FlushLargeStoresPolicy is used and there are multiple column families, then every time that we hit the total memstore limit, we find out all the column families whose memstores exceed a "lower bound" and only flush them while retaining the others in memory.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The "lower bound" will be "hbase.hregion.memstore.flush.size / column_family_number" by default unless value of this property is larger than that.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If none of the families have their memstore size more than lower bound, all the memstores will be flushed (just as usual).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If the memstores in a region are this size or larger when we go to close, run a "pre-flush" to clear out memstores before we put up the region closed flag and take the region offline.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] On close, a flush is run under the close flag to empty memory.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] During this time the region is offline and we are not taking on any writes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If the memstore content is large, this flush could take a long time to complete.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The preflush is meant to clean out the bulk of the memstore before putting up the close flag and taking the region offline so the flush that runs under the close flag has little to do.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Block updates if memstore has hbase.hregion.memstore.block.multiplier times hbase.hregion.memstore.flush.size bytes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Useful preventing runaway memstore during spikes in update traffic.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Without an upper-bound, memstore fills such that when it flushes the resultant flush files take a long time to compact or split, or worse, we OOME.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Enables the MemStore-Local Allocation Buffer, a feature which works to prevent heap fragmentation under heavy write loads.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] This can reduce the frequency of stop-the-world GC pauses on large heaps.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The maximum byte size of a chunk in the MemStoreLAB.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The amount of off-heap memory all MemStores in a RegionServer may use.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A value of 0 means that no off-heap memory will be used and all chunks in MSLAB will be HeapByteBuffer, otherwise the non-zero value means how many megabyte of off-heap memory will be used for chunks in MSLAB and all chunks in MSLAB will be DirectByteBuffer.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The maximal size of one allocation in the MemStoreLAB, if the desired byte size exceed this threshold then it will be just allocated from JVM heap rather than MemStoreLAB.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If the sum of the sizes of a region’s HFiles has grown to exceed this value, the region is split in two.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] There are two choices of how this option works, the first is when any store’s size exceed the threshold then split, and the other is overall region’s size exceed the threshold then split, it can be configed by hbase.hregion.split.overallfiles.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If we should sum overall region files size when check to split.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Time between major compactions, expressed in milliseconds.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Set to 0 to disable time-based automatic major compactions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] User-requested and size-based major compactions will still run.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] This value is multiplied by hbase.hregion.majorcompaction.jitter to cause compaction to start at a somewhat-random time during a given window of time.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The default value is 7 days, expressed in milliseconds.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If major compactions are causing disruption in your environment, you can configure them to run at off-peak times for your deployment, or disable time-based major compactions by setting this parameter to 0, and run major compactions in a cron job or by another external mechanism.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A multiplier applied to hbase.hregion.majorcompaction to cause compaction to occur a given amount of time either side of hbase.hregion.majorcompaction.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The smaller the number, the closer the compactions will happen to the hbase.hregion.majorcompaction interval.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If more than or equal to this number of StoreFiles exist in any one Store (one StoreFile is written per flush of MemStore), a compaction is run to rewrite all StoreFiles into a single StoreFile.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Larger values delay compaction, but when compaction does occur, it takes longer to complete.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Enable/disable compactions on by setting true/false.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] We can further switch compactions dynamically with the compaction_switch shell command.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] With fewer threads, the MemStore flushes will be queued.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] With more threads, the flushes will be executed in parallel, increasing the load on HDFS, and potentially causing more compactions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If more than this number of StoreFiles exist in any one Store (one StoreFile is written per flush of MemStore), updates are blocked for this region until a compaction is completed, or until hbase.hstore.blockingWaitTime has been exceeded.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The time for which a region will block updates after reaching the StoreFile limit defined by hbase.hstore.blockingStoreFiles.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] After this time has elapsed, the region will stop blocking updates even if a compaction has not been completed.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The minimum number of StoreFiles which must be eligible for compaction before compaction can run.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The goal of tuning hbase.hstore.compaction.min is to avoid ending up with too many tiny StoreFiles to compact.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Setting this value to 2 would cause a minor compaction each time you have two StoreFiles in a Store, and this is probably not appropriate.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If you set this value too high, all the other values will need to be adjusted accordingly.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] For most cases, the default value is appropriate (empty value here, results in 3 by code logic).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] In previous versions of HBase, the parameter hbase.hstore.compaction.min was named hbase.hstore.compactionThreshold.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The maximum number of StoreFiles which will be selected for a single minor compaction, regardless of the number of eligible StoreFiles.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Effectively, the value of hbase.hstore.compaction.max controls the length of time it takes a single compaction to complete.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Setting it larger means that more StoreFiles are included in a compaction.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] For most cases, the default value is appropriate.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A StoreFile (or a selection of StoreFiles, when using ExploringCompactionPolicy) smaller than this size will always be eligible for minor compaction.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] HFiles this size or larger are evaluated by hbase.hstore.compaction.ratio to determine if they are eligible.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If this parameter is lowered, the ratio check is triggered more quickly.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] This addressed some issues seen in earlier versions of HBase but changing this parameter is no longer necessary in most situations.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A StoreFile (or a selection of StoreFiles, when using ExploringCompactionPolicy) larger than this size will be excluded from compaction.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The effect of raising hbase.hstore.compaction.max.size is fewer, larger StoreFiles that do not get compacted often.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If you feel that compaction is happening too often without much benefit, you can try raising this value.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Default: the value of LONG.MAX_VALUE, expressed in bytes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] For minor compaction, this ratio is used to determine whether a given StoreFile which is larger than hbase.hstore.compaction.min.size is eligible for compaction.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Its effect is to limit compaction of large StoreFiles.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The value of hbase.hstore.compaction.ratio is expressed as a floating-point decimal.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A large ratio, such as 10, will produce a single giant StoreFile.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Conversely, a low value, such as .25, will produce behavior similar to the BigTable compaction algorithm, producing four StoreFiles.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A moderate value of between 1.0 and 1.4 is recommended.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] When tuning this value, you are balancing write costs with read costs.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Raising the value (to something like 1.4) will have more write costs, because you will compact larger StoreFiles.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] However, during reads, HBase will need to seek through fewer StoreFiles to accomplish the read.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Consider this approach if you cannot take advantage of Bloom filters.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Otherwise, you can lower this value to something like 1.0 to reduce the background cost of writes, and use Bloom filters to control the number of StoreFiles touched during reads.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Allows you to set a different (by default, more aggressive) ratio for determining whether larger StoreFiles are included in compactions during off-peak hours.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Works in the same way as hbase.hstore.compaction.ratio.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Only applies if hbase.offpeak.start.hour and hbase.offpeak.end.hour are also enabled.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The amount of time to delay purging of delete markers with future timestamps.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If unset, or set to 0, all delete markers, including those with future timestamps, are purged during the next major compaction.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Otherwise, a delete marker is kept until the major compaction which occurs after the marker’s timestamp plus the value of this setting, in milliseconds.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The start of off-peak hours, expressed as an integer between 0 and 23, inclusive.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The end of off-peak hours, expressed as an integer between 0 and 23, inclusive.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] There are two different thread pools for compactions, one for large compactions and the other for small compactions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] This helps to keep compaction of lean tables (such as hbase:meta) fast.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If a compaction is larger than this threshold, it goes into the large compaction pool.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] In most cases, the default value is appropriate.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Default: 2 x hbase.hstore.compaction.max x hbase.hregion.memstore.flush.size (which defaults to 128MB).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The value field assumes that the value of hbase.hregion.memstore.flush.size is unchanged from the default.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Specifies whether to drop pages read/written into the system page cache by major compactions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Setting it to true helps prevent major compactions from polluting the page cache, which is almost always required, especially for clusters with low/moderate memory to storage ratio.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Specifies whether to drop pages read/written into the system page cache by minor compactions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Setting it to true helps prevent minor compactions from polluting the page cache, which is most beneficial on clusters with low memory to storage ratio or very write heavy clusters.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] You may want to set it to false under moderate to low write workload when bulk of the reads are on the most recently written data.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The maximum number of KeyValues to read and then write in a batch when flushing or compacting.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Set this lower if you have big KeyValues and problems with Out Of Memory Exceptions Set this higher if you have wide, small rows.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Enables StoreFileScanner parallel-seeking in StoreScanner, a feature which can reduce response latency under special conditions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The default thread pool size if parallel-seeking feature enabled.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The eviction policy for the L1 block cache (LRU or TinyLFU).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Percentage of maximum heap (-Xmx setting) to allocate to block cache used by a StoreFile.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Set to 0 to disable but it’s not recommended; you need at least enough cache to hold the storefile indices.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Defines the maximum heap memory allocated for the HFile block cache, specified in bytes or human-readable formats like '10m' for megabytes or '10g' for gigabytes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] This configuration allows setting an absolute memory size instead of a percentage of the maximum heap.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Takes precedence over hfile.block.cache.size if both are specified.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] This allows to put non-root multi-level index blocks into the block cache at the time the index is being written.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] When the size of a leaf-level, intermediate-level, or root-level index block in a multi-level block index grows to this size, the block is written out and a new block is started.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Where to store the contents of the bucketcache.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] One of: offheap, file, files, mmap or pmem.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If a file or files, set it to file(s):PATH_TO_FILE. mmap means the content will be in an mmaped file.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] 'pmem' is bucket cache over a file on the persistent memory device.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] See offheap.blockcache for more information.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The target lower bound on aggregate compaction throughput, in bytes/sec.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Allows you to tune the minimum available compaction throughput when the PressureAwareCompactionThroughputController throughput controller is active.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The target upper bound on aggregate compaction throughput, in bytes/sec.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Allows you to control aggregate compaction throughput demand when the PressureAwareCompactionThroughputController throughput controller is active.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] (It is active by default.) The maximum throughput will be tuned between the lower and upper bounds when compaction pressure is within the range [0.0, 1.0].
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If compaction pressure is 1.0 or greater the higher bound will be ignored until pressure returns to the normal range.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] It is the total capacity in megabytes of BucketCache.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] A comma-separated list of sizes for buckets for the bucketcache.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] List block sizes in order from smallest to largest.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The sizes you use will depend on your data access patterns.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Must be a multiple of 256 else you will run into 'java.io.IOException: Invalid HFile block magic' when you go to read from cache.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] If you specify no values here, then you pick up the default bucketsizes set in code (See BucketAllocator#DEFAULT_BUCKET_SIZES).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] The HFile format version to use for new files.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Version 3 adds support for tags in hfiles (See #hbase.tags).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p03] Also see the configuration 'hbase.replication.rpc.codec'.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Enables cache-on-write for inline blocks of a compound Bloom filter.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The size in bytes of a single block ("chunk") of a compound Bloom filter.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This size is approximate, because Bloom blocks can only be inserted at data block boundaries, and the number of keys per data block varies.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Whether an HFile block should be added to the block cache when the block is finished.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This is for the RPC layer to define how long (millisecond) HBase client applications take for a remote call to time out.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] It uses pings to check connections but will eventually throw a TimeoutException.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Operation timeout is a top-level restriction (millisecond) that makes sure a blocking operation in Table will not be blocked more than this.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] In each operation, if rpc request fails because of timeout or other reason, it will retry until success or throw RetriesExhaustedException.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] But if the total time being blocking reach the operation timeout before retries exhausted, it will break early and throw SocketTimeoutException.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Interval in milliseconds of checking and invalidating meta cache when table disabled or dropped, when set to zero means disable checking, suggest set it to 24h or a higher value, because disable/delete table usually not very frequently.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The number of cells scanned in between heartbeat checks.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Heartbeat checks occur during the processing of scans to determine whether or not the server should stop scanning in order to send back a heartbeat message to the client.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Heartbeat messages are used to keep the client-server connection alive during long running scans.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Small values mean that the heartbeat checks will occur more often and thus will provide a tighter bound on the execution time of the scan.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This is another version of "hbase.rpc.timeout".
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] For those RPC operation within cluster, we rely on this configuration to set a short timeout limitation for short operation.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] For example, short rpc timeout for region server’s trying to report to active master can benefit quicker master failover process.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This config is for experts: don’t set its value unless you really know what you are doing.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] When set to a non-empty value, this represents the (external facing) hostname for the underlying server.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] See https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-12954 for details.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] When set to true, regionserver will use the current node hostname for the servername and HMaster will skip reverse DNS lookup and use the hostname sent by regionserver instead.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Note that this config and hbase.unsafe.regionserver.hostname are mutually exclusive.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] See https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-18226 for more details.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Full path to the kerberos keytab file to use for logging in the configured HMaster server principal.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The kerberos principal name that should be used to run the HMaster process.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The principal name should be in the form: user/hostname@DOMAIN.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If "_HOST" is used as the hostname portion, it will be replaced with the actual hostname of the running instance.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Full path to the kerberos keytab file to use for logging in the configured HRegionServer server principal.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The kerberos principal name that should be used to run the HRegionServer process.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The policy configuration file used by RPC servers to make authorization decisions on client requests.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Only used when HBase security is enabled.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] List of users or groups (comma-separated), who are allowed full privileges, regardless of stored ACLs, across the cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Group names should be prefixed with "@".
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The update interval for master key for authentication tokens in servers in milliseconds.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The maximum lifetime in milliseconds after which an authentication token expires.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] When a client is configured to attempt a secure connection, but attempts to connect to an insecure server, that server may instruct the client to switch to SASL SIMPLE (unsecure) authentication.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This setting controls whether or not the client will accept this instruction from the server.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] When false (the default), the client will not allow the fallback to SIMPLE authentication, and will abort the connection.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] When a server is configured to require secure connections, it will reject connection attempts from clients using SASL SIMPLE (unsecure) authentication.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This setting allows secure servers to accept SASL SIMPLE connections from clients when the client requests.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] When false (the default), the server will not allow the fallback to SIMPLE authentication, and will reject the connection.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] WARNING: This setting should ONLY be used as a temporary measure while converting clients over to secure authentication.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] It MUST BE DISABLED for secure operation.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] When set to true, HBase client using SASL Kerberos will skip reverse DNS lookup and use provided hostname of the destination for the principal instead.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] See https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-25665 for more details.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] When this is set to true the webUI and such will display all start/end keys as part of the table details, region names, etc.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] When this is set to false, the keys are hidden.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Enables or disables coprocessor loading.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If 'false' (disabled), any other coprocessor related configuration will be ignored.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Enables or disables user (aka. table) coprocessor loading.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If 'false' (disabled), any table coprocessor attributes in table descriptors will be ignored.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If "hbase.coprocessor.enabled" is 'false' this setting has no effect.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] A comma-separated list of region observer or endpoint coprocessors that are loaded by default on all tables.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] For any override coprocessor method, these classes will be called in order.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] After implementing your own Coprocessor, add it to HBase’s classpath and add the fully qualified class name here.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] A coprocessor can also be loaded on demand by setting HTableDescriptor or the HBase shell.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] A comma-separated list of org.apache.hadoop.hbase.coprocessor.MasterObserver coprocessors that are loaded by default on the active HMaster process.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] For any implemented coprocessor methods, the listed classes will be called in order.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] After implementing your own MasterObserver, just put it in HBase’s classpath and add the fully qualified class name here.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Set to true to cause the hosting server (master or regionserver) to abort if a coprocessor fails to load, fails to initialize, or throws an unexpected Throwable object.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Setting this to false will allow the server to continue execution but the system wide state of the coprocessor in question will become inconsistent as it will be properly executing in only a subset of servers, so this is most useful for debugging only.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Defines the mode the REST server will be started in.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Possible values are: false: All HTTP methods are permitted - GET/PUT/POST/DELETE. true: Only the GET method is permitted.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The maximum number of threads of the REST server thread pool.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Threads in the pool are reused to process REST requests.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This controls the maximum number of requests processed concurrently.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] It may help to control the memory used by the REST server to avoid OOM issues.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If the thread pool is full, incoming requests will be queued up and wait for some free threads.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The minimum number of threads of the REST server thread pool.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The thread pool always has at least these number of threads so the REST server is ready to serve incoming requests.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Enables running the REST server to support proxy-user mode.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Set to true to skip the 'hbase.defaults.for.version' check.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Setting this to true can be useful in contexts other than the other side of a maven generation; i.e. running in an IDE.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Set to true to enable locking the table in zookeeper for schema change operations.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Table locking from master prevents concurrent schema modifications to corrupt table state.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Maximum size of single row in bytes (default is 1 Gb) for Get’ting or Scan’ning without in-row scan flag set.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If row size exceeds this limit RowTooBigException is thrown to client.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] New threads are created on every connection until this many threads are created.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] When the pending request queue overflows, new threads are created until their number reaches this number.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] After that, the server starts dropping connections.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The maximum number of pending Thrift connections waiting in the queue.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If there are no idle threads in the pool, the server queues requests.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Only when the queue overflows, new threads are added, up to hbase.thrift.maxQueuedRequests threads.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Use Thrift TFramedTransport on the server side.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This is the recommended transport for thrift servers and requires a similar setting on the client side.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Changing this to false will select the default transport, vulnerable to DoS when malformed requests are issued due to THRIFT-601.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Use Thrift TCompactProtocol binary serialization protocol.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] FS Permissions for the root data subdirectory in a secure (kerberos) setup.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] When master starts, it creates the rootdir with this permissions or sets the permissions if it does not match.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] FS Permissions for the root WAL directory in a secure(kerberos) setup.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] When master starts, it creates the WAL dir with this permissions or sets the permissions if it does not match.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Set to true to allow snapshots to be taken / restored / cloned.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Set to true to take a snapshot before the restore operation.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The snapshot taken will be used in case of failure, to restore the previous state.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Name of the failsafe snapshot taken by the restore operation.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] You can use the {snapshot.name}, {table.name} and {restore.timestamp} variables to create a name based on what you are restoring.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Location where the snapshotting process will occur.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The location of the completed snapshots will not change, but the temporary directory where the snapshot process occurs will be set to this location.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This can be a separate filesystem than the root directory, for performance increase purposes.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The number that determines how often we scan to see if compaction is necessary.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Normally, compactions are done after some events (such as memstore flush), but if region didn’t receive a lot of writes for some time, or due to different compaction policies, it may be necessary to check it periodically.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The interval between checks is hbase.server.compactchecker.interval.multiplier multiplied by hbase.server.thread.wakefrequency.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] How long we wait on dfs lease recovery in total before giving up.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] How long between dfs recover lease invocations.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Should be larger than the sum of the time it takes for the namenode to issue a block recovery command as part of datanode; dfs.heartbeat.interval and the time it takes for the primary datanode, performing block recovery to timeout on a dead datanode; usually dfs.client.socket-timeout.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] New column family descriptors will use this value as the default number of versions to keep.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If set to true, this configuration parameter enables short-circuit local reads.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This is a path to a UNIX domain socket that will be used for communication between the DataNode and local HDFS clients, if dfs.client.read.shortcircuit is set to true.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If the string "_PORT" is present in this path, it will be replaced by the TCP port of the DataNode.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Be careful about permissions for the directory that hosts the shared domain socket; dfsclient will complain if open to other users than the HBase user.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If the DFSClient configuration dfs.client.read.shortcircuit.buffer.size is unset, we will use what is configured here as the short circuit read default direct byte buffer size.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] DFSClient native default is 1MB; HBase keeps its HDFS files open so number of file blocks * 1MB soon starts to add up and threaten OOME because of a shortage of direct memory.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Make it > the default hbase block size set in the HColumnDescriptor which is usually 64k.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If set to true (the default), HBase verifies the checksums for hfile blocks.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] HBase writes checksums inline with the data when it writes out hfiles.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] HDFS (as of this writing) writes checksums to a separate file than the data file necessitating extra seeks.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Checksum verification by HDFS will be internally disabled on hfile streams when this flag is set.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If the hbase-checksum verification fails, we will switch back to using HDFS checksums (so do not disable HDFS checksums!
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] And besides this feature applies to hfiles only, not to WALs).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If this parameter is set to false, then hbase will not verify any checksums, instead it will depend on checksum verification being done in the HDFS client.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Number of bytes in a newly created checksum chunk for HBase-level checksums in hfile blocks.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Name of an algorithm that is used to compute checksums.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Possible values are NULL, CRC32, CRC32C.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Maximum number of bytes returned when calling a scanner’s next method.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Note that when a single row is larger than this limit the row is still returned completely.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The default value is 2MB, which is good for 1ge networks.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] With faster and/or high latency networks this value should be increased.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This setting activates the publication by the master of the status of the region server.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] When a region server dies and its recovery starts, the master will push this information to the client application, to let them cut the connection immediately instead of waiting for a timeout.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Implementation of the status publication with a multicast message.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Implementation of the status listener with a multicast message.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Multicast address to use for the status publication by multicast.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Multicast port to use for the status publication by multicast.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The directory from which the custom filter JARs can be loaded dynamically by the region server without the need to restart.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] However, an already loaded filter/co-processor class would not be un-loaded.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Controls whether or not secure authentication is enabled for HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Possible values are 'simple' (no authentication), and 'kerberos'.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Class used to execute the regions balancing when the period occurs.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] See the class comment for more on how it works http://hbase.apache.org/devapidocs/org/apache/hadoop/hbase/master/balancer/StochasticLoadBalancer.html It replaces the DefaultLoadBalancer as the default (since renamed as the SimpleLoadBalancer).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Factor Table name when the balancer runs.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Class used to execute the region normalization when the period occurs.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] A comma-separated list of regular expressions used to match against an HTTP request’s User-Agent header when protection against cross-site request forgery (CSRF) is enabled for REST server by setting hbase.rest.csrf.enabled to true.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If the incoming User-Agent matches any of these regular expressions, then the request is considered to be sent by a browser, and therefore CSRF prevention is enforced.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If the request’s User-Agent does not match any of these regular expressions, then the request is considered to be sent by something other than a browser, such as scripted automation.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] In this case, CSRF is not a potential attack vector, so the prevention is not enforced.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This helps achieve backwards-compatibility with existing automation that has not been updated to send the CSRF prevention header.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] EXEC privilege, like any other permission, can be granted globally to a user, or to a user on a per table or per namespace basis.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] For more information on coprocessor endpoints, see the coprocessor section of the HBase online manual.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] For more information on granting or revoking permissions using the AccessController, see the security section of the HBase online manual.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] A comma-separated list of org.apache.hadoop.hbase.procedure.RegionServerProcedureManager procedure managers that are loaded by default on the active HRegionServer process.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The lifecycle methods (init/start/stop) will be called by the active HRegionServer process to perform the specific globally barriered procedure.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] After implementing your own RegionServerProcedureManager, just put it in HBase’s classpath and add the fully qualified class name here.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] A comma-separated list of org.apache.hadoop.hbase.procedure.MasterProcedureManager procedure managers that are loaded by default on the active HMaster process.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] A procedure is identified by its signature and users can use the signature and an instant name to trigger an execution of a globally barriered procedure.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] After implementing your own MasterProcedureManager, just put it in HBase’s classpath and add the fully qualified class name here.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Fully qualified name of class implementing coordinated state manager.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The period (in milliseconds) for refreshing the store files for the secondary regions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Secondary regions sees new files (from flushes and compactions) from primary once the secondary region refreshes the list of files in the region (there is no notification mechanism).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] But too frequent refreshes might cause extra Namenode pressure.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If the files cannot be refreshed for longer than HFile TTL (hbase.master.hfilecleaner.ttl) the requests are rejected.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Configuring HFile TTL to a larger value is also recommended with this setting.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Whether asynchronous WAL replication to the secondary region replicas is enabled or not.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] We have a separated implementation for replicating the WAL without using the general inter-cluster replication framework, so now we will not add any replication peers.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Each class in the list must extend org.apache.hadoop.hbase.http.FilterInitializer.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The corresponding Filter will be initialized.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Then, the Filter will be applied to all user facing jsp and servlet web pages.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The ordering of the list defines the ordering of the filters.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The default StaticUserWebFilter add a user principal as defined by the hbase.http.staticuser.user property.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The maximum number of threads that the HTTP Server will create in its ThreadPool.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Comma separated list of servlet names to enable for metrics collection.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The codec that is to be used when replication is enabled so that the tags are also replicated.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This is used along with HFileV3 which supports tags in them.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If tags are not used or if the hfile version used is HFileV2 then KeyValueCodec can be used as the replication codec.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Note that using KeyValueCodecWithTags for replication when there are no tags causes no harm.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The maximum number of threads any replication source will use for shipping edits to the sinks in parallel.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This also limits the number of chunks each replication batch is broken into.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Larger values can improve the replication throughput between the master and slave clusters.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The default of 10 will rarely need to be changed.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The user name to filter as, on static web filters while rendering content.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] An example use is the HDFS web UI (user to be used for browsing files).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The percent of region server RPC threads failed to abort RS. -1 Disable aborting; 0 Abort if even a single handler has died; 0.x Abort only when this percent of handlers have died; 1 Abort only all of the handers have died.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Number of opened file handlers to cache.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] A larger value will benefit reads by providing more file handlers per mob file cache and would reduce frequent file opening and closing.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] However, if this is set too high, this could lead to a "too many opened file handlers" The default value is 1000.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The amount of time in seconds before the mob cache evicts cached mob files.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The ratio (between 0.0 and 1.0) of files that remains cached after an eviction is triggered when the number of cached mob files exceeds the hbase.mob.file.cache.size.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The period that MobFileCleanerChore runs.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The MOB file name uses only the date part of the file creation time in it.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] We use this time for deciding TTL expiry of the files.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] So the removal of TTL expired files might be delayed.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The max number of a MOB table regions that is allowed in a batch of the mob compaction.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] By setting this number to a custom value, users can control the overall effect of a major compaction of a large MOB-enabled table.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The period that MobCompactionChore runs.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Timeout for master for the snapshot procedure execution.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Timeout for regionservers to keep threads in snapshot request pool waiting.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Number of rows in a batch operation above which a warning will be logged.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If hbase.client.write.buffer.maxmutations is not set, this will be used as fallback for that setting.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Snapshot Cleanup chore interval in milliseconds.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The cleanup thread keeps running at this interval to find all snapshots that are expired based on TTL and delete them.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Default Snapshot TTL to be considered when the user does not specify TTL while creating snapshot.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Regions Recovery Chore interval in milliseconds.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This chore keeps running at this interval to find all regions with configurable max store file ref count and reopens them.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Very large number of ref count on a compacted store file indicates that it is a ref leak on that object(compacted store file).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Such files can not be removed after it is invalidated via compaction.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Only way to recover in such scenario is to reopen the region which can release all resources, like the refcount, leases, etc.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This config represents Store files Ref Count threshold value considered for reopening regions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Any region with compacted store files ref count > this value would be eligible for reopening by master.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Here, we get the max refCount among all refCounts on all compacted away store files that belong to a particular region.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Default value -1 indicates this feature is turned off.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Only positive integer value should be provided to enable this feature.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Default size of ringbuffer to be maintained by each RegionServer in order to store online slowlog responses.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This is an in-memory ring buffer of requests that were judged to be too slow in addition to the responseTooSlow logging.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The in-memory representation would be complete.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Indicates whether RegionServers have ring buffer running for storing Online Slow logs in FIFO manner with limited entries.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The size of the ring buffer is indicated by config: hbase.regionserver.slowlog.ringbuffer.size The default value is false, turn this on and get latest slowlog responses with complete data.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Should be enabled only if hbase.regionserver.slowlog.buffer.enabled is enabled.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If enabled (true), all slow/large RPC logs would be persisted to system table hbase:slowlog (in addition to in-memory ring buffer at each RegionServer).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The records are stored in increasing order of time.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Operators can scan the table with various combination of ColumnValueFilter.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Maximum regions to merge at a time when we fix overlaps noted in CJ consistency report, but avoid merging 100 regions in one go!
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If value is true, RegionServer will abort batch requests of Put/Delete with number of rows in a batch operation exceeding threshold defined by value of config: hbase.rpc.rows.warning.threshold.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The default value is false and hence, by default, only warning will be logged.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This config should be turned on to prevent RegionServer from serving very large batch size of rows and this way we can improve CPU usages by discarding too large batch request.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Default values for NamedQueueService implementors.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This comma separated full class names represent all implementors of NamedQueueService that we would like to be invoked by LogEvent handler service.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] One example of NamedQueue service is SlowLogQueueService which is used to store slow/large RPC logs in ringbuffer at each RegionServer.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Indicates whether active HMaster has ring buffer running for storing balancer decisions in FIFO manner with limited entries.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Indicates whether active HMaster has ring buffer running for storing balancer rejection in FIFO manner with limited entries.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If true, derive StoreFile locality metrics from the underlying DFSInputStream backing reads for that StoreFile.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This value will update as the DFSInputStream’s block locations are updated over time.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Otherwise, locality is computed on StoreFile open, and cached until the StoreFile is closed.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If deriving StoreFile locality metrics from the underlying DFSInputStream, how long should the derived values be cached for.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The derivation process may involve hitting the namenode, if the DFSInputStream’s block list is incomplete.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Set HBase environment variables in this file.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Examples include options to pass the JVM on start of an HBase daemon such as heap size and garbage collector configs.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] You can also set configurations for HBase configuration, log directories, niceness, ssh options, where to locate process pid files, etc.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Open the file at *conf/hbase-env.sh* and peruse its content.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Add your own environment variables here if you want them read by HBase daemons on startup.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Changes here will require a cluster restart for HBase to notice the change.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Since version 2.5.0, HBase has upgraded to Log4j2, so the configuration file name and format has changed.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Edit this file to change rate at which HBase files are rolled and to change the level at which HBase logs messages.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Changes here will require a cluster restart for HBase to notice the change though log levels can be changed for particular daemons via the HBase UI.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If you are running HBase in standalone mode, you don’t need to configure anything for your client to work provided that they are all on the same machine.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Starting release 3.0.0, the default connection registry has been switched to a rpc based implementation.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Refer to Rpc Connection Registry (new as of 2.5.0) for more details about what a connection registry is and implications of this change.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Depending on your HBase version, following is the expected minimal client configuration.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] In 2.x.y releases, the default connection registry was based on ZooKeeper as the source of truth.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This means that the clients always looked up ZooKeeper znodes to fetch the required metadata.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] For example, if an active master crashed and the a new master is elected, clients looked up the master znode to fetch the active master address (similarly for meta locations).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This meant that the clients needed to have access to ZooKeeper and need to know the ZooKeeper ensemble information before they can do anything.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The default implementation was switched to a rpc based connection registry.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] With this implementation, by default clients contact the active or stand-by master RPC end points to fetch the connection registry information.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] This means that the clients should have access to the list of active and master end points before they can do anything.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The configuration value for *hbase.masters* is a comma separated list of *host:port* values.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If no port value is specified, the default of *16000* is assumed.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The configuration value for *hbase.client.bootstrap.servers* is a comma separated list of *host:port* values.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Notice that port must be specified here.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Usually these configurations are kept out in the *hbase-site.xml* and is picked up by the client from the `CLASSPATH`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If you are configuring an IDE to run an HBase client, you should include the *conf/* directory on your classpath so *hbase-site.xml* settings can be found (or add *src/test/resources* to pick up the hbase-site.xml used by tests).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The configuration used by a Java client is kept in an HBaseConfiguration instance.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] It is also possible to specify configuration directly without having to read from a *hbase-site.xml*.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] HBase provides a wide variety of timeout settings to limit the execution time of various remote operations.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The `hbase.rpc.timeout` property limits how long a single RPC call can run before timing out.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] To fine tune read or write related RPC timeouts set `hbase.rpc.read.timeout` and `hbase.rpc.write.timeout` configuration properties.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] In the absence of these properties `hbase.rpc.timeout` will be used.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] A higher-level timeout is `hbase.client.operation.timeout` which is valid for each client call.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] When an RPC call fails for instance for a timeout due to `hbase.rpc.timeout` it will be retried until `hbase.client.operation.timeout` is reached.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Client operation timeout for system tables can be fine tuned by setting `hbase.client.meta.operation.timeout` configuration value.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] When this is not set its value will use `hbase.client.operation.timeout`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Timeout for scan operations is controlled differently.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Use `hbase.client.scanner.timeout.period` property to set this timeout.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Here is a basic configuration example for a distributed ten node cluster: * The nodes are named `example0`, `example1`, etc., through node `example9` in this example.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] * The HBase Master and the HDFS NameNode are running on the node `example0`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] * RegionServers run on nodes `example1`-`example9`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] * A 3-node ZooKeeper ensemble runs on `example1`, `example2`, and `example3` on the default ports.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] * ZooKeeper data is persisted to the directory */export/zookeeper*.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Below we show what the main configuration files — *hbase-site.xml*, *regionservers*, and *hbase-env.sh* — found in the HBase *conf* directory might look like.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] In this file you list the nodes that will run RegionServers.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] In our case, these nodes are `example1`-`example9`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] The following lines in the *hbase-env.sh* file show how to set the `JAVA_HOME` environment variable (required for HBase) and set the heap to 4 GB (rather than the default value of 1 GB).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] If you copy and paste this example, be sure to adjust the `JAVA_HOME` to suit your environment.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p04] Use rsync to copy the content of the *conf* directory to all nodes of the cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Below we list some *important* configurations.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] We’ve divided this section into required configuration and worth-a-look recommended configs.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] If you have a cluster with a lot of regions, it is possible that a Regionserver checks in briefly after the Master starts while all the remaining RegionServers lag behind.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] This first server to check in will be assigned all regions which is not optimal.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] To prevent the above scenario from happening, up the `hbase.master.wait.on.regionservers.mintostart` property from its default value of 1.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] See HBASE-6389 Modify the conditions to ensure that Master waits for sufficient number of Region Servers before starting region assignments for more detail.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The default timeout is 90 seconds (specified in milliseconds).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] This means that if a server crashes, it will be 90 seconds before the Master notices the crash and starts recovery.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] You might need to tune the timeout down to a minute or even less so the Master notices failures sooner.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Before changing this value, be sure you have your JVM garbage collection configuration under control, otherwise, a long garbage collection that lasts beyond the ZooKeeper session timeout will take out your RegionServer.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] (You might be fine with this — you probably want recovery to start on the server if a RegionServer has been in GC for a long period of time).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] To change this configuration, edit *hbase-site.xml*, copy the changed file across the cluster and restart.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] We set this value high to save our having to field questions up on the mailing lists asking why a RegionServer went down during a massive import.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The usual cause is that their JVM is untuned and they are running into long GC pauses.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Our thinking is that while users are getting familiar with HBase, we’d save them having to know all of its intricacies.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Later when they’ve built some confidence, then they can play with configuration such as this.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] This is the "…number of volumes that are allowed to fail before a DataNode stops offering service.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] By default, any volume failure will cause a datanode to shutdown" from the *hdfs-default.xml* description.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] You might want to set this to about half the amount of your available disks.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] This setting defines the number of threads that are kept open to answer incoming requests to user tables.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The rule of thumb is to keep this number low when the payload per request approaches the MB (big puts, scans using a large cache) and high when the payload is small (gets, small puts, ICVs, deletes).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The total size of the queries in progress is limited by the setting `hbase.ipc.server.max.callqueue.size`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] It is safe to set that number to the maximum number of incoming clients if their payload is small, the typical example being a cluster that serves a website since puts aren’t typically buffered and most of the operations are gets.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The reason why it is dangerous to keep this setting high is that the aggregate size of all the puts that are currently happening in a region server may impose too much pressure on its memory, or even trigger an OutOfMemoryError.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] A RegionServer running on low memory will trigger its JVM’s garbage collector to run more frequently up to a point where GC pauses become noticeable (the reason being that all the memory used to keep all the requests' payloads cannot be trashed, no matter how hard the garbage collector tries).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] After some time, the overall cluster throughput is affected since every request that hits that RegionServer will take longer, which exacerbates the problem even more.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] You can get a sense of whether you have too little or too many handlers by rpc.logging on an individual RegionServer then tailing its logs (Queued requests consume memory).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] HBase ships with a reasonable, conservative configuration that will work on nearly all machine types that people might want to test with.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] If you have larger machines — HBase has 8G and larger heap — you might find the following configuration options helpful.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] You should consider enabling ColumnFamily compression.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] There are several options that are near-frictionless and in most all cases boost performance by reducing the size of StoreFiles and thus reducing I/O.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] HBase uses wal to recover the memstore data that has not been flushed to disk in case of an RS failure.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] These WAL files should be configured to be slightly smaller than HDFS block (by default a HDFS block is 64Mb and a WAL file is ~60Mb).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] HBase also has a limit on the number of WAL files, designed to ensure there’s never too much data that needs to be replayed during recovery.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] This limit needs to be set according to memstore configuration, so that all the necessary data would fit.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] It is recommended to allocate enough WAL files to store at least that much data (when all memstores are close to full).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] For example, with 16Gb RS heap, default memstore settings (0.4), and default WAL file size (~60Mb), 16Gb*0.4/60, the starting point for WAL file count is ~109.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] However, as all memstores are not expected to be full all the time, less WAL files can be allocated.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] HBase generally handles splitting of your regions based upon the settings in your *hbase-default.xml* and *hbase-site.xml* configuration files.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Important settings include `hbase.regionserver.region.split.policy`, `hbase.hregion.max.filesize`, `hbase.regionserver.regionSplitLimit`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] A simplistic view of splitting is that when a region grows to `hbase.hregion.max.filesize`, it is split.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] For most usage patterns, you should use automatic splitting.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] See manual region splitting decisions for more information about manual region splitting.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Instead of allowing HBase to split your regions automatically, you can choose to manage the splitting yourself.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Manually managing splits works if you know your keyspace well, otherwise let HBase figure where to split for you.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Manual splitting can mitigate region creation and movement under load.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] It also makes it so region boundaries are known and invariant (if you disable region splitting).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] If you use manual splits, it is easier doing staggered, time-based major compactions to spread out your network IO load.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The optimal number of pre-split regions depends on your application and environment.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] A good rule of thumb is to start with 10 pre-split regions per server and watch as data grows over time.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] It is better to err on the side of too few regions and perform rolling splits later.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The optimal number of regions depends upon the largest StoreFile in your region.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The size of the largest StoreFile will increase with time if the amount of data grows.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The goal is for the largest region to be just large enough that the compaction selection algorithm only compacts it during a timed major compaction.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Otherwise, the cluster can be prone to compaction storms with a large number of regions under compaction at the same time.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] It is important to understand that the data growth causes compaction storms and not the manual split decision.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] If the regions are split into too many large regions, you can increase the major compaction interval by configuring `HConstants.MAJOR_COMPACTION_PERIOD`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The `org.apache.hadoop.hbase.util.RegionSplitter` utility also provides a network-IO-safe rolling split of all regions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] By default, major compactions are scheduled to run once in a 7-day period.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] If you need to control exactly when and how often major compaction runs, you can disable managed major compactions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] See the entry for `hbase.hregion.majorcompaction` in the compaction.parameters table for details.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Speculative Execution of MapReduce tasks is on by default, and for HBase clusters it is generally advised to turn off Speculative Execution at a system-level unless you need it for a specific case, where it can be configured per-job.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Set the properties `mapreduce.map.speculative` and `mapreduce.reduce.speculative` to false.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The balancer is a periodic operation which is run on the master to redistribute regions on the cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] It is configured via `hbase.balancer.period` and defaults to 300000 (5 minutes).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] See master.processes.loadbalancer for more information on the LoadBalancer.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Do not turn off block cache (You’d do it by setting `hfile.block.cache.size` to zero).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Currently, we do not do well if you do this because the RegionServer will spend all its time loading HFile indices over and over again.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] If your working set is such that block cache does you no good, at least size the block cache such that HFile indices will stay up in the cache (you can get a rough idea on the size you need by surveying RegionServer UIs; you’ll see index block size accounted near the top of the webpage).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] If a big 40ms or so occasional delay is seen in operations against HBase, try the Nagles' setting.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] For example, see the user mailing list thread, Inconsistent scan performance with caching set to 1 and the issue cited therein where setting `notcpdelay` improved scan speeds.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] You might also see the graphs on the tail of HBASE-7008 Set scanner caching to a better default where our Lars Hofhansl tries various data sizes w/ Nagle’s on and off measuring the effect.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] This section is about configurations that will make servers come back faster after a fail.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] See the Deveraj Das and Nicolas Liochon blog post Introduction to HBase Mean Time to Recover (MTTR) for a brief introduction.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The issue HBASE-8354 forces Namenode into loop with lease recovery requests is messy but has a bunch of good discussion toward the end on low timeouts and how to cause faster recovery including citation of fixes added to HDFS.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The below suggested configurations are Varun’s suggestions distilled and tested.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Make sure you are running on a late-version HDFS so you have the fixes he refers to and himself adds to HDFS that help HBase MTTR (e.g.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] HDFS-3703, HDFS-3712, and HDFS-4791 — Hadoop 2 for sure has them and late Hadoop 1 has some).
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] And on the NameNode/DataNode side, set the following to enable 'staleness' introduced in HDFS-3703, HDFS-3912.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] JMX (Java Management Extensions) provides built-in instrumentation that enables you to monitor and manage the Java VM.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] To enable monitoring and management from remote systems, you need to set system property `com.sun.management.jmxremote.port` (the port number through which you want to enable JMX RMI connections) when you start the Java VM.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] See the official documentation for more information.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Historically, besides above port mentioned, JMX opens two additional random TCP listening ports, which could lead to port conflict problem.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] As an alternative, you can use the coprocessor-based JMX implementation provided by HBase.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Currently it supports Master and RegionServer Java VM.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The registry port can be shared with connector port in most cases, so you only need to configure `regionserver.rmi.registry.port`.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] However, if you want to use SSL communication, the 2 ports must be configured to different values.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] By default the password authentication and SSL communication is disabled.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] See example password/access file under *$JRE_HOME/lib/management*.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] It is possible to change a subset of the configuration without requiring a server restart.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] In the HBase shell, the operations `update_config`, `update_all_config` and `update_rsgroup_config` will prompt a server, all servers or all servers in the RSGroup to reload configuration.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Only a subset of all configurations can currently be changed in the running server.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] You cannot skip major versions when upgrading.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] If you are upgrading from version 0.98.x to 2.x, you must first go from 0.98.x to 1.2.x and then go from 1.2.x to 2.x.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Review Apache HBase Configuration, in particular Hadoop.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Familiarize yourself with Support and Testing Expectations.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Starting with the 1.0.0 release, HBase is working towards Semantic Versioning for its release versioning.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] In addition to the usual API versioning considerations HBase has other compatibility dimensions that we need to consider.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] HBase has a lot of API points, but for the compatibility matrix above, we differentiate between Client API, Limited Private API, and Private API.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] HBase uses Apache Yetus Audience Annotations to guide downstream expectations for stability.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] HBase Client API consists of all the classes or methods that are marked with InterfaceAudience.Public interface.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] All main classes in hbase-client and dependent modules have either InterfaceAudience.Public, InterfaceAudience.LimitedPrivate, or InterfaceAudience.Private marker.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Not all classes in other modules (hbase-server, etc) have the marker.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] If a class is not annotated with one of these, it is assumed to be a InterfaceAudience.Private class.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] LimitedPrivate annotation comes with a set of target consumers for the interfaces.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Those consumers are coprocessors, phoenix, replication endpoint implementations or similar.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] At this point, HBase only guarantees source and binary compatibility for these interfaces between patch versions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] All classes annotated with InterfaceAudience.Private or all classes that do not have the annotation are for HBase internal use only.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The interfaces and method signatures can change at any point in time.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] If you are relying on a particular interface that is marked Private, you should open a jira to propose changing the interface to be Public or LimitedPrivate, or an interface exposed for this purpose.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] When we say two HBase versions are compatible, we mean that the versions are wire and binary compatible.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Compatible HBase versions means that clients can talk to compatible but differently versioned servers.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] It means too that you can just swap out the jars of one version and replace them with the jars of another, compatible version and all will just work.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Unless otherwise specified, HBase point versions are (mostly) binary compatible.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] You can safely do rolling upgrades between binary compatible versions; i.e. across maintenance releases: e.g. from 1.4.4 to 1.4.6.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] See Does compatibility between versions also mean binary compatibility? discussion on the HBase dev mailing list.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] A rolling upgrade is the process by which you update the servers in your cluster a server at a time.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] You can rolling upgrade across HBase versions if they are binary or wire compatible.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] See Rolling Upgrade Between Versions that are Binary/Wire Compatible for more on what this means.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Coarsely, a rolling upgrade is a graceful stop each server, update the software, and then restart.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] You do this for each server in the cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Usually you upgrade the Master first and then the RegionServers.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] See Rolling Restart for tools that can help use the rolling upgrade process.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] For example, in the below, HBase was symlinked to the actual HBase install.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The rolling-restart script will first gracefully stop and restart the master, and then each of the RegionServers in turn.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Because the symlink was changed, on restart the server will come up using the new HBase version.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Check logs for errors as the rolling upgrade proceeds.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Unless otherwise specified, HBase minor versions are binary compatible.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] You can do a Rolling Upgrades between HBase point versions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] For example, you can go to 1.4.4 from 1.4.6 by doing a rolling upgrade across the cluster replacing the 1.4.4 binary with a 1.4.6 binary.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] In the minor version-particular sections below, we call out where the versions are wire/protocol compatible and in this case, it is also possible to do a Rolling Upgrades.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Sometimes things don’t go as planned when attempting an upgrade.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] This section explains how to perform a *rollback* to an earlier HBase release.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Note that this should only be needed between Major and some Minor releases.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] You should always be able to *downgrade* between HBase Patch releases within the same Minor version.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] These instructions may require you to take steps before you start the upgrade process, so be sure to read through this section beforehand.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] This section describes how to perform a *rollback* on an upgrade between HBase minor and major versions.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] In this document, rollback refers to the process of taking an upgraded cluster and restoring it to the old version *while losing all changes that have occurred since upgrade*.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] By contrast, a cluster *downgrade* would restore an upgraded cluster to the old version while maintaining any data written since the upgrade.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] We currently only offer instructions to rollback HBase clusters.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Further, rollback only works when these instructions are followed prior to performing the upgrade.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] When these instructions talk about rollback vs downgrade of prerequisite cluster services (i.e.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] HDFS), you should treat leaving the service version the same as a degenerate case of downgrade.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Unless you are doing an all-service rollback, the HBase cluster will lose any configured peers for HBase replication.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] If your cluster is configured for HBase replication, then prior to following these instructions you should document all replication peers.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] After performing the rollback you should then add each documented peer back to the cluster.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] For more information on enabling HBase replication, listing peers, and adding a peer see Managing and Configuring Cluster Replication.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Note also that data written to the cluster since the upgrade may or may not have already been replicated to any peers.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Determining which, if any, peers have seen replication data as well as rolling back the data in those peers is out of the scope of this guide.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Unless you are doing an all-service rollback, going through a rollback procedure will likely destroy all locality for Region Servers.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] You should expect degraded performance until after the cluster has had time to go through compactions to restore data locality.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Optionally, you can force a compaction to speed this process up at the cost of generating cluster load.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] The instructions below assume default locations for the HBase data directory and the HBase znode.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Both of these locations are configurable and you should verify the value used in your cluster before proceeding.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] In the event that you have a different value, just replace the default with the one found in your configuration * HBase data directory is configured via the key 'hbase.rootdir' and has a default value of '/hbase'.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] * HBase znode is configured via the key 'zookeeper.znode.parent' and has a default value of '/hbase'.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] If you will be performing a rollback of both the HDFS and ZooKeeper services, then HBase’s data will be rolled back in the process.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] No additional steps are needed pre-upgrade.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] As an extra precautionary measure, you may wish to use distcp to back up the HBase data off of the cluster to be upgraded.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] To do so, follow the steps in the 'Before upgrade' section of 'Rollback after HDFS downgrade' but copy to another HDFS instance instead of within the same instance.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] Verify HBase contents—use the HBase shell to list tables and scan some known values.
[src:apache-hbase/book-p05] If you will be rolling back HDFS but going through a ZooKeeper downgrade, then HBase will be in an inconsistent state.
